commit_message:
Add transactional test support to provisioning

This patch further reorganizes ProvisionedDatabase
such that it now can maintain a single ProvisionedDatabase
instance across a named "scope".  A "scope" refers
to a series of test runs which can all safely share the
same database schema as well as optional fixture data.

When a test specifies a non-None "scope", the test
is run within a special context that redirects
engine and connection use to a new series of objects
based on a hierarchy called NonCommittingConnectable.
This object produces a facade that behaves like
SQLAlchemy Engine, Connection and Transaction objects
to the degree necessary for a typical database round-trip
test, but ensures that all operations run within a
single transaction that is never committed.   To allow
tests to do real rollbacks, savepoints are used, and the
transaction container always maintains a savepoint
as well for this purpose.

As tests run, if each successive test indicates the
same "scope" as the previous, the database is not dropped,
and the same schema is re-used; all changes to this schema
since the last test ran will have been rolled back.

When a change in scope occurs between tests, the
"drop all objects" routine is run, again so that the
database is not actually dropped, but is instead cleared
of all objects built within it.

Currently, the behavior of ProvisionedDatabase
as a persistent object between tests is only meaningful within
the span of a testr run that calls upon the
testr "instance_execute" and related hooks.  If these
hooks are not called, such as if the tests are run
via a different test runner, or from testtools directly,
there is currently no way for the
provisioning system to have an indication to drop
databases when all tests are complete, so without
instance_execute setting up OSLO_SCHEMA_TOKEN, the
old behavior of dropping the named database after
each test still takes place.  The ProvisionedDatabase
instance ties its own lifecycle to that of the named database
which it creates; so when dropping the database, the
ProvisionedDatabase itself removes it from the lookup.
On the next lookup for that type of database, a new
ProvisionedDatabase will replace it.

The default scope for any test is None, which
indicates that the scoping feature is not used for
those tests.  However, assuming testr has specified
OSLO_SCHEMA_TOKEN, the ProvisionedDatabase instance is now
persistent across runs for these tests as well, but at
the end of each test it now runs the "drop all objects"
routine, rather than dropping the whole database.

Change-Id: I3bca012e2c7655b60cde7085ea55df365219edba

Alexei Kornienko - IMHO this is not "vendor lock", the testr specific code is present only in testr.conf.   the tests continue to run without issue in other systems.

to support other test runners, we'd ideally integrate with their parallel run systems as well.   to my knowledge, nose does not support a parallel run system.  py.test does, and if we were to support this we would use conftest.py in order to set up nodes in a way that is compatible with xdist (see https://github.com/zzzeek/sqlalchemy/blob/54592942c4a9c3d6d891519082555f8081026445/lib/sqlalchemy/testing/plugin/pytestplugin.py#L47 for SQLAlchemy's approach using pytest).	 

at the moment openstack is pretty deeply locked in with testr, I regularly use py.test against it so i am in favor of support of other test runners.   

I'm pretty -1 on shell scripts since they are too open-ended, bypass the environmental features of various test runner environments and can't really make good assumptions.  For example, it appears that this ceilometer script is run as a wrapper - what if tests are run with a different number of workers, or run without using workers?   The test runner knows this based on arguments we pass to it (like -n <num> to pytest/xdist) - the shell script can't know about these options, unless..it parses for them, and is therefore locked in to that runner, or it has its own argument system, which has to be translated to the runner, and is again locked into that runner!  Test-runner-specific assumptions leak into these files very easily, whereas including explicit integration with selected runners eliminates that possibility.'}, {'account_id': 11816, 'date': '2014-08-08 15:03:48.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8: Workflow-1

i think i need to figure out why in multi-run mode we aren't getting issues with tables being dropped, as this doesnt yet include dropping tables.   HMMMmmmm..."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-08-08 15:04:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8: Verified+1

So the layering here doesn't make sense to me - this will mean you can't run the tests without testr

The instance provisioning hooks are intended for provisioning VMs / LXC containers / chroots or containers on other machines - things that the test framework being run shouldn't reasonably know about.

Local resources like a stub mysql/postgresql cluster can be trivially created within a python test process, one per process, in a just in time fashion, and that IME works very well. See e.g. https://pypi.python.org/pypi/testing.postgresql/1.0.4 or https://pypi.python.org/pypi/van.pg/2.0 which has built in testresources support."}, {'account_id': 1, 'date': '2014-08-22 01:28:08.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 21: Code-Review-1

I agree with lifeless; we've fought hard to avoid requiring a specific test runner, and it's still the case that not all OpenStack projects have migrated to testr yet.

Nodepool has a mechanism to create a per-test database that does not require testr-specific stuff.  Perhaps we could borrow from there."}, {'account_id': 11816, 'date': '2014-08-22 02:48:28.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 21:

OK there seems to be a common thread of misunderstanding with this patch, as people keep thinking this is somehow hardcoding to testr.  Let it be known that this is entirely incorrect, as well as that I *despise* testr, and I'd much prefer we use pytest.  



1. this patch in no way affects the ability of the tests to be run with any runner you want.  I run them with pytest all the time.   You can run the tests any way you want, and it just so happens that if an environment variable specifies OSLO_SCHEMA_TOKEN, it will just happen to use a database of that name, rather than a new name per test.   Any test runner you'd like can set this variable and call upon a setup/teardown to create test databases.

2. Currently, to my knowledge there is *no documented system* of running openstack tests *in parallel* with any other runner rather than testr.   Of course, pytest can do it also and so can others, but at the moment, *every project is using testr*, just look at this simple grep:

./barbican/.testr.conf
./ceilometer/.testr.conf
./ceilometer/nova_tests/.testr.conf
./cinder/.testr.conf
./gantt/.testr.conf
./glance/.testr.conf
./heat/.testr.conf
./ironic/.testr.conf
./keystone/.testr.conf
./marconi/.testr.conf
./neutron/.testr.conf
./nova/.testr.conf
./oslo-incubator/.testr.conf
./oslo-specs/.testr.conf
./oslo.config/.testr.conf
./oslo.db/.testr.conf
./oslo.messaging/.testr.conf
./oslo.utils/.testr.conf
./oslotest/.testr.conf
./python-keystoneclient/.testr.conf
./python-novaclient/.testr.conf
./requirements/.testr.conf
./sahara/.testr.conf
./taskflow/.testr.conf
./tempest/.testr.conf
./trove/.testr.conf
./tuskar/.testr.conf


Additionally, all of these projects *hardcode*, yes *hardcode* to testr in their tox.ini:

$ find . -name tox.ini -exec grep -l testr {} \;
./barbican/tox.ini
./ceilometer/tox.ini
./cinder/tox.ini
./gantt/tox.ini
./glance/tox.ini
./heat/tox.ini
./ironic/tox.ini
./keystone/tox.ini
./marconi/tox.ini
./neutron/tox.ini
./nova/tox.ini
./oslo-incubator/tox.ini
./oslo.config/tox.ini
./oslo.db/tox.ini
./oslo.messaging/tox.ini
./oslo.utils/tox.ini
./oslotest/tox.ini
./python-keystoneclient/tox.ini
./python-novaclient/tox.ini
./requirements/tox.ini
./sahara/tox.ini
./taskflow/tox.ini
./tempest/tox.ini
./trove/tox.ini
./tuskar/tox.ini

so I'm just very confused why everyone seems to suggest that *this particular patch* is what's hardcoding us to testr - simply because of three lines added to the testr.conf, that are there for no other reason than to *integrate the existing system into testr*.


The simple fact is that a system is required to set up and tear down these databases at the beginning and the end of the entire test run.  The tests currently need to run with testr.  So adding those three lines to .testr.conf is the *only way to do it*.

if we'd like to change the test runner, that's great, and in fact, *most of this patch is not affected by that*.  All the logic here can integrated into whatever shell script or other test platform you want, and if we'd like to support other test systems, that is totally fine by me.  Let me know what they are and the appropriate hooks into provision.py can be added for those as well, *in later patches*.

Once again.  *you can run the tests any way you want with this patch, no functionality is being removed*.

thanks for reading!"}, {'account_id': 11816, 'date': '2014-08-22 03:06:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 21:

lifeless: checked out the two pypi packages.  testing.postgresql is hardcoded to postgresql, emits a kill for the whole PG process for termination, and only integrates with the testing hooks you give it.    So it isn't providing any solution to the three lines in .testr.conf here.


van.pg, also postgresql specific, uses testresources.TestResourceManager, which seems nice, but again, the key thing we need here is a means of tearing things down after a whole suite of tests have run, that is, not at every test tearDown, but when the suite ends, it has to run.  The lazy initialization is not the challenge here, the system here already does that.

Someone suggested using an atexit() hook to do the teardown.  I haven't played with that but I fear it might not be very stable.    My suggestion so far has been to integrate with whatever number of test runners are desired, to the degree that runs with those runners desire the "persistent database" feature.  This feature is entirely optional.  Without it, you get ad-hoc databases just like we always have.'}, {'account_id': 11816, 'date': '2014-08-22 03:12:16.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 21:

one more comment, this also might not be clear and I was not accurate in my first comment - the system *creates the databases on demand only* - the "init" process here only goes through the step of creating random string names for the databases, so that they can be passed to the "drop" process at the end.   The drop process does actually drop those databases that were created.  But the create step for the databases is *within* the running of the tests, not ahead of time.

the only hook that this system needs is a reliable "we're done running tests" hook.  that's it.   A simple shell script can be added to do these steps for other runners, or if the system has decent hooks like pytest's conftest.py.  testr just happens to provide this one system (and no other, unless we want to dramatically alter how we are using tox + testr to require injection of a shell script).'}, {'account_id': 11816, 'date': '2014-08-22 03:20:15.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 21:

I guess what I can do here is radically alter the commit message as well as the comments in the code, which casually refer to "testr" as the actor that is doing the work here.  This is not really accurate, the provisioning system does the work.   I can only guess that's where the perception that this is a testr lock-in is coming from.'}, {'account_id': 11816, 'date': '2014-08-22 03:47:25.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 22.'}, {'account_id': 11816, 'date': '2014-08-22 04:11:38.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 23.'}, {'account_id': 4190, 'date': '2014-08-22 04:47:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 23: Code-Review-1

@michael, testresources tears things down at the end of the last test that needed it, giving precisely the optimisation you want.'}, {'account_id': 11816, 'date': '2014-08-22 04:55:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 23:

OK, is that because testr recognizes some special hook within it?   if so, does this hook work with other runners?   or otherwise what mechanism allows it to run at the end of all tests regardless of test runner?'}, {'account_id': 4190, 'date': '2014-08-22 05:14:40.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 23:

This is the heart of it - http://bazaar.launchpad.net/~testresources-developers/testresources/trunk/view/head:/lib/testresources/__init__.py#L187 - OptimisingTestSuite.

This decorates an entire suite (so to the best of my knowledge it runs with any test collection that follows the unittest suite contains suite-or-tests model), topologically sorts them by the resources they need (so e.g. all mysql tests would run together, all postgresql would run together). At the end of a test, if the next test doesn't require a resource, the resource is torn down."}, {'account_id': 11816, 'date': '2014-08-22 05:16:22.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 23:

it looks like it is doing stack frame inspection in teardown, looking for the TestResult object and then poking inside of that somehow, to figure out something about the scope of tests outside of it.   It's not really clear.    If everyone wants me to use this, that would be fine since we've already established dependencies on the various testtools-related libraries, for example i have to use testscenarios for the next step in this series.   I have observed that a lot of this stuff is questionable with py.test as py.test does kind of an end-run around a lot of unittest's expected behaviors.  Can't say for sure in this case."}, {'account_id': 11816, 'date': '2014-08-22 05:22:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 23:

Also keep in mind the next step here is to use testscenarios so that a single test can be run against multiple backends.  I've looked at the source of that, and it instruments the unittest test runner to multiply tests *after* tests have been gathered.   So by definition if testresources requires that different resources are used serially, it won't play nicely with testscenarios.

Overall testresources seems awfully complicated and very magic (just look at http://bazaar.launchpad.net/~testresources-developers/testresources/trunk/view/head:/lib/testresources/__init__.py#L787 for starters) for something that is quite simple if the test suite just allows for a "process tear down" step.   What test environment are we anticipating that doesn't offer such a feature ?   so far it looks like tests are always run either via testr or shell script.'}, {'account_id': 11816, 'date': '2014-08-22 05:34:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 23:

I'm pretty certain they play nice together ;) They way we'll be hooking them up is with load_tests, wherein the tests are multiplied after gathering - as you say - the mutiplied tests are then handed to testresources OTS and that will reorder them to group by the fixtures needed - and in fact in this case we'll probably end up setting the fixtures attribute as part of the scenario.

Just questions in the comments.'}, {'account_id': 4190, 'date': '2014-08-28 03:59:23.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 23:

Hi, I totally get your frustration, I gave feedback as soon as I was pointed at your patch :(.

I've now yak shaved the issues with discover preventing the solution being trivial: http://bugs.python.org/issue16662 has a patch on it which corrects the behaviour of load_tests in a package, and https://github.com/testing-cabal/testtools/pull/98 backports that to testtools so that we can use it on existing releases of Python.

With that in place, the glue will look like this:

in $projectname/test/__init__.py
 def load_tests(loader, found_tests, pattern):
     this_dir = os.path.dirname(__file__)
     pkg_tests = loader.discover(start_dir=this_dir, pattern=pattern)
     # optimise order (e.g. group by scenario etc)
     result = OptimisingTestSuite()
     # apply scenarios
     result.addTest(generate_scenarios(found_tests))
     result.addTest(generate_scenarios(pkg_tests))
     return result

This will take effect as long as the discover test loader is used."}, {'account_id': 11816, 'date': '2014-08-28 18:41:52.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 23:

OK so testtools needs to be released in order for this to work?   

Would we perhaps want to consider only adding tests that we know to have "resources" to the optimising test suite, and all the rest just pass through as is?  This would minimize the impact on existing tests.

Please review my blueprint for this at https://review.openstack.org/#/c/117335/, thanks!'}, {'account_id': 4190, 'date': '2014-08-29 00:33:15.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 23:

Yes, testtools release is coming.

Adding all the tests is conceptually a lot easier - and the OTS is designed to cope.'}, {'account_id': 4190, 'date': '2014-08-29 02:00:46.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 23:

testtools 0.9.39 should do what you need in a straightforward fashion. revisions:
[{'created': '2014-07-29 22:36:00.000000000', 'message': 'Use testr instance provisioning to lazily create databases

This patch makes use of testr's instance_provision utility
to provide for on-demand database backends that then stay
persistent for the remainder of the individual test process.
During provisioning, "oslo.db.sqlalchemy.provision echo"
generates random database identifiers, but doesn't actually
create real databases.   As these identifiers are passed to
test processes via OSLO_SCHEMA_TOKEN, the ProvisionedDatabase()
object will emit CREATE DATABASE for a given token when
a database of that backend and token is first requested; the
database then stays created until the testr instance dispose
phase, and ProvisionedDatabase also holds onto the Engine
so that expensive engine-initialization is kept to a minimum.
After test completion, testr calls into
"oslo.db.sqlalchemy.provision drop" with each name, whereupon
the databases given are dropped only if they exist.

Control of database connectivity remains via the
OS_TEST_DBAPI_ADMIN_CONNECTION environment variable.  When not
set, connectivity defaults to sqlite://, plus those backends
found to be available using "opportunistic" naming conventions.
When the variable is present, it provides a semicolon-delimited
list of URLs, and only those URLs will be used for initial
connectivity.

Change-Id: Ibaaefcef2678cc5b985e7c00f05f91b6f02de3f8
Partially-Closes-Bug: 1339206

to provide for on-demand database backends that then stay
persistent for the remainder of the individual test process.
During provisioning, "oslo.db.sqlalchemy.provision echo"
generates random database identifiers, but doesn't actually
create real databases.   As these identifiers are passed to
test processes via OSLO_SCHEMA_TOKEN, the ProvisionedDatabase()
object will emit CREATE DATABASE for a given token when
a database of that backend and token is first requested; the
database then stays created until the testr instance dispose
phase, and ProvisionedDatabase also holds onto the Engine
so that expensive engine-initialization is kept to a minimum.
After test completion, testr calls into
"oslo.db.sqlalchemy.provision drop" with each name, whereupon
the databases given are dropped only if they exist.

Control of database connectivity remains via the
OS_TEST_DBAPI_ADMIN_CONNECTION environment variable.  When not
set, connectivity defaults to sqlite://, plus those backends
found to be available using "opportunistic" naming conventions.
When the variable is present, it provides a semicolon-delimited
list of URLs, and only those URLs will be used for initial
connectivity.

Change-Id: Ibaaefcef2678cc5b985e7c00f05f91b6f02de3f8

'}, {'created': '2014-08-22 03:47:25.000000000', 'message': 'Add support for per-test-run database provisioning

A key aspect of being able to use so-called "tranasctional"
testing, that is, testing where the same schema is maintained
across many tests, and data created by the tests is
kept within a non-persistent transaction, is that a single
database node be made available for the duration of many
tests.   The issue that has occurred with this approach
however is that when the tests are run using
multiple, concurrent processes, the concurrent tests
conflict and lock against each other if they are run against
the same database at the same time.

Therefore, this patch provides an all new and optional
system of providing for individual, per-process databases
that last for the lifespan of when they are first needed
until the entire test suite completes.

The entry point for this system is that an environment
variable OSLO_SCHEMA_TOKEN is established local to a
particular test process.  Concurrent test processes would
each have a different value for OSLO_SCHEMA_TOKEN.

If OSLO_SCHEMA_TOKEN is not set, then the system works
in "ad-hoc" mode, which is exactly how the test runner
has always worked; an ad-hoc database when requested is
created as needed, typically during test setup, and
it is then dropped within the test's cleanup/teardown
phase, that is, the database is created/dropped per test.
This is roughly how openstack database tests run today in any case, so to
that degree, this patch does not remove any existing behavior,
it merely adds an option for an alternative system of
allowing the database to remain persistently, when OSLO_SCHEMA_TOKEN
is used.

The provisioning system within each process will then
create a database of this name for a particular backend
when a database for that backend is requested; for example,
if a test fixture requires a "postgresql" database and
the value of OSLO_SCHEMA_TOKEN is "xyz", a new postgresql
database "xyz" is created once, and then re-used for all
subsequent tests that request the same type of backend.

The databases can then be dropped by calling upon the
"drop" command at the end of the test run, which can be passed
any number of ad-hoc database names to be dropped; names that
weren't actually created for a particular backend are skipped
so it can be safely called with a full set of names even if
those names were not all used for all backends.

Since the system deals with databases that last throughout
the entire run of tests, running with different kinds of
test runners requires that some kind of "at the end of all
tests" hook be established that will emit the drop command.
There are many ways that this can be achieved, and most test
runners also supply some built-in system of providing such a
hook.  However, there is currently no "standard" system for this
within openstack test suites, and this patch does not attempt
to solve that particular issue across the board.  Approaches
include integration with test runners such as py.test's conftest.py
mechanism, or the use of shell scripts.

As openstack tests have to a large extent standardized on the
use of the testr test runner, at least within continuous integration
systems, integration is proposed here to integrate the system
with testr when it runs, by using the "instance provisioning"
feature of testr and calling upon the "drop" script within
.testr.conf, as well as running an "echo" script to generate
database names up front so that they can be passed through
testr's system.    testr to my knowledge offers no other mechanism for
invoking a global "teardown" feature that runs at the end of each
test process as a whole; if such a system does exist, it can
be proposed in lieu of using .testr.conf.

However it should be noted that the testr integration proposed
here in no way precludes the system from being integrated
with any number of other runners, nor does it imply that
the tests can no longer run with other runners, as the
patch here only offers OSLO_SCHEMA_TOKEN as an optional system,
disabled by default.   Any mechanism that can run a "cleanup"
step at the end of a full test run can be integrated with
the concept here trivially.

Change-Id: Ibaaefcef2678cc5b985e7c00f05f91b6f02de3f8
Partial-Bug: #1339206

commit_message:
Add support for per-test-run database provisioning

A key aspect of being able to use so-called "tranasctional"
testing, that is, testing where the same schema is maintained
across many tests, and data created by the tests is
kept within a non-persistent transaction, is that a single
database node be made available for the duration of many
tests.   The issue that has occurred with this approach
however is that when the tests are run using
multiple, concurrent processes, the concurrent tests
conflict and lock against each other if they are run against
the same database at the same time.

Therefore, this patch provides an all new and optional
system of providing for individual, per-process databases
that last for the lifespan of when they are first needed
until the entire test suite completes.

The entry point for this system is that an environment
variable OSLO_SCHEMA_TOKEN is established local to a
particular test process.  Concurrent test processes would
each have a different value for OSLO_SCHEMA_TOKEN.

If OSLO_SCHEMA_TOKEN is not set, then the system works
in "ad-hoc" mode, which is exactly how the test runner
has always worked; an ad-hoc database when requested is
created as needed, typically during test setup, and
it is then dropped within the test's cleanup/teardown
phase, that is, the database is created/dropped per test.
This is roughly how openstack database tests run today in any case, so to
that degree, this patch does not remove any existing behavior,
it merely adds an option for an alternative system of
allowing the database to remain persistently, when OSLO_SCHEMA_TOKEN
is used.

The provisioning system within each process will then
create a database of this name for a particular backend
when a database for that backend is requested; for example,
if a test fixture requires a "postgresql" database and
the value of OSLO_SCHEMA_TOKEN is "xyz", a new postgresql
database "xyz" is created once, and then re-used for all
subsequent tests that request the same type of backend.

The databases can then be dropped by calling upon the
"drop" command at the end of the test run, which can be passed
any number of ad-hoc database names to be dropped; names that
weren't actually created for a particular backend are skipped
so it can be safely called with a full set of names even if
those names were not all used for all backends.

Since the system deals with databases that last throughout
the entire run of tests, running with different kinds of
test runners requires that some kind of "at the end of all
tests" hook be established that will emit the drop command.
There are many ways that this can be achieved, and most test
runners also supply some built-in system of providing such a
hook.  However, there is currently no "standard" system for this
within openstack test suites, and this patch does not attempt
to solve that particular issue across the board.  Approaches
include integration with test runners such as py.test's conftest.py
mechanism, or the use of shell scripts.

As openstack tests have to a large extent standardized on the
use of the testr test runner, at least within continuous integration
systems, integration is proposed here to integrate the system
with testr when it runs, by using the "instance provisioning"
feature of testr and calling upon the "drop" script within
.testr.conf, as well as running an "echo" script to generate
database names up front so that they can be passed through
testr's system.    testr to my knowledge offers no other mechanism for
invoking a global "teardown" feature that runs at the end of each
test process as a whole; if such a system does exist, it can
be proposed in lieu of using .testr.conf.

However it should be noted that the testr integration proposed
here in no way precludes the system from being integrated
with any number of other runners, nor does it imply that
the tests can no longer run with other runners, as the
patch here only offers OSLO_SCHEMA_TOKEN as an optional system,
disabled by default.   Any mechanism that can run a "cleanup"
step at the end of a full test run can be integrated with
the concept here trivially.

Change-Id: Ibaaefcef2678cc5b985e7c00f05f91b6f02de3f8
Partial-Bug: #1339206

commit_message:
Adds "/var/log/messages" to hourly log rotation

Because still many services, including MongoDB, are logging to standard log
destination we should rotate the logs more agressively. Moreover MongoDB in
version 2.4 cannot use LogFacility, so it's easier to fix it in logrotate than
in MonngoDB module itself.

Change-Id: Ice1bbf4a3bf2d453a41d7660b8742a074ec29216
Closes-Bug: 1367234
(cherry picked from commit f686e9ea00eaa9ae141e283ff2b8b28bacd89f72)

[{'created': '2014-08-18 21:06:30.000000000', 'message': 'Add swift store upload recover

During segmented (chunked) uploads of large files to Swift, if a
single segment fails to upload, Glance will abort the entire
upload, which could have been in progress for many hours.

However, if seek() and tell() methods are provided on the input
file stream, swiftclient will attempt to reset the filestream
back to the beginning of the segment and retry.

This patch adds glance.store.swift.BufferedReader to provide this
reset capability.  It works by buffering the segment/chunk in memory
in case an upload error occurs and a reset is required.  This could
potentially use a much larger amount of memory, so a CONF setting,
CONF.swift_store_reader_class is required to enable the new reader.
(The default is to use the existing glance.store.swift.ChunkReader.)

Change-Id: I7d7337cee930fd2fb451fa5c7093c5fa9f985dcb
Closes-Bug: 1235386

commit_message:
Add swift store upload recovery

During segmented (chunked) uploads of large files to Swift, if a
single segment fails to upload, Glance will abort the entire
upload, which could have been in progress for many hours.

However, if seek() and tell() methods are provided on the input
file stream, swiftclient will attempt to reset the filestream
back to the beginning of the segment and retry.

This patch adds glance.store.swift.BufferedReader to provide this
reset capability.  It works by buffering the segment/chunk in memory
in case an upload error occurs and a reset is required.  This could
potentially use a much larger amount of memory, so a CONF setting,
CONF.swift_store_reader_class is required to enable the new reader.
(The default is to use the existing glance.store.swift.ChunkReader.)

Change-Id: I7d7337cee930fd2fb451fa5c7093c5fa9f985dcb
Closes-Bug: 1235386
DocImpact

commit_message:
Adds "/var/log/messages" to hourly log rotation

Because still many services, including MongoDB, are logging to standard log
destination we should rotate the logs more agressively. Moreover MongoDB in
version 2.4 cannot use LogFacility, so it's easier to fix it in logrotate than
in MonngoDB module itself.

Change-Id: Ice1bbf4a3bf2d453a41d7660b8742a074ec29216
Closes-Bug: 1367234
(cherry picked from commit f686e9ea00eaa9ae141e283ff2b8b28bacd89f72)

commit_message:
Forbid remove all controllers at once

We need to forbid remove all controllers even you add new one at the
same time, since it affects cluster's availability.

(cherry picked from commit ac23dc36eecbcbb5aba202dbcc63fbf774149dae)

Change-Id: I9d1ac51981d0516937aa21e04e66e2cca03022ef
Closes-Bug: #1367001

commit_message:
Auto generate the API documentation

Once we use the pbr based build to generate files, we prune
the indexes to remove references to code we would like to
hide like the common modules and private modules in conf.py.
We reuse the same excluded_patterns variable that is already
used in Sphinx and filter these modules from autoindex.rst

Change-Id: Iace038faf5d2a22bf797f5cbb9433ff027b2101e

commit_message:
Add Keystone URI to 401 responces

Instead of using a catch-all "Swift" authentication scheme, if
keystone client provides HTTP_X_AUTH_URI or auth_uri is specified
in the [filter:keystoneauth], the Keystone uri is returned.

Closes-Bug: 1349364
Change-Id: I27105cbcabb471d6cfd580cf9d98dc1388886aba

commit_message:
labs: exit if ssh returns error value

With this changeset, osbash host scripts abort installation over ssh if
script execution in the VM returns an error. The patch has no effect on
installations using VirtualBox guest-addons.

Change-Id: Ibc0b297f44289cfe37e07fad1c0fcef1a30abfb2

'}]
commit_message:
Make fedora-rdo-icehouse-repository more generic

Nothing tied this element to be Fedora only. It can also be used for
RHEL. And it could also be used for any RDO release not just icehouse.

There fore this element has been renamed to rdo-repository.

Removed the element-deps that was including the "fedora" element.
Updated the README to make it clearer that it could be used for both
Fedora and RHEL.

Change-Id: I8724203de7c37f083ab3f6cf4cdd134946f643da

commit_message:
Adds information about regular expressions for Compute API

- when searching for a name, regexp is used for server name,
not xsd:string.
- hoping to convey this difference with a paragraph as well
as changing xsd:string to regexp in the parameter table.

Closes-bug: 1365227
Change-Id: Idd8bea413ab4581e495cd4ee58d4a2d8554e62bc

commit_message:
Forbid remove all controllers at once

We need to forbid remove all controllers even you add new one at the
same time, since it affects cluster's availability.

Change-Id: I9d1ac51981d0516937aa21e04e66e2cca03022ef
Closes-Bug: #1367001

commit_message:
handles keyboard interrupt

When an user intentionally provides an keyboard interrupt, ironicclient
throws the entire traceback on to the terminal instead of handling it.
ironicclient will now handle the keyboard interrrupt and provides an crisp
message on to the terminal.

Change-Id: I8e657dc0cf64fa3396fb8fd32c5ffb57016ce864
Closes-Bug: #1367283

commit_message:
Rally needs bumping python-novaclient

python-novaclient <= 2.17 doesn't support authentification via
auth_token (at least without specifing username and password)

Which was changed here:
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/85920/

So it makes sense to bump version of novaclient

Change-Id: I6d2a0a414b89e757a48d6616c8e74ed34591d02b

commit_message:
Remove test_correct_has from our test suite

This test is not reliable. Whenever it's executed outside a git repo or
with a repo that has uncommited changes, it fails. Since this code has
been stable for quite some time and it won't likely change in the
future, I think it's safe to remove this test.

Change-Id: I39a3dbd01ef189571f6dcf3ab4cd7a476733950a

[{'created': '2014-09-11 14:52:52.000000000', 'message': "Don't import client from the version package

zaqar client has a client discovery function that should be used instead
of the client module in the version package. This patch fixes that issue
in our benchmark tool by importing the right client module.

Change-Id: I294e56cedd8fd0a9ec7f4cc01d8396fd3edb2335
"}]
commit_message:
Don't import client from the version package

zaqar client has a client discovery function that should be used instead
of the client module in the version package. This patch fixes that issue
in our benchmark tool by importing the right client module.

Change-Id: I294e56cedd8fd0a9ec7f4cc01d8396fd3edb2335

commit_message:
Document mod_wsgi doesn't support chunked encoding

Document in logical places that keystone under mod_wsgi will not
support chunked encoding.

Change-Id: I957059be560fa65e2f0d5166d9490b2c7bab9f17
Closes-Bug: #1346211

commit_message:
Fix issue with intermittent test failures in test_pkg.py

The test failures were a result of randomized test order and the way
in which these tests were setting up mocks for pexpect.spawn.expect
and pexpect.spawn.match.

The code now mocks pexpect.spawn and then sets return values and match
in each test as appropriate. Code in setUp establishes a patch and a
cleanUp function is added to reverse the patch. No code is required in
tearDown as a result.

execute() was being Mocked using code in setUp and tearDown and this
was replaced that with a similar patch in setUp with a corresponding
cleanUp function to reverse its effects.

Since we're close to Juno, I've not gone down the path of converting
this test to use a fixture which would further reduce duplicated code.

Change-Id: I3edfd499823f2c2f4591e709384a24f1b55abe5a
Closes-Bug: 1365531

commit_message:
Add entry-point for oslo.config options and update registering logic

1. The change exposed all options of store and driver by oslo.config
entry-point.
2. Refactor store and driver options registering logic to leverage this
unified option discover function.

Change-Id: Ibbd0f27abd0c0eb9a88d8d30de1e89264a11f53d
Signed-off-by: Zhi Yan Liu <zhiyanl@cn.ibm.com>

commit_message:
Libvirt-Enable support for discard option for disk device

Support setting discard option for instance's disk.
If discard option is enabled, unused/freed blocks can be return back to the
storage device.

blueprint libvirt-disk-discard-option
DocImpact: Add a new configuration in nova.conf

Change-Id: Ic87b9348a2e441d5df0b468bb88ec6e77f8b4ce2

Right - the concerns in tripleo were:

 - we shouldn't be changing the ports that swift has chosen
 - what port plumbing within a cloud lives on is not a user level parameter for deploying a cloud - its trivia and we should handle it via automation.

If swift is choosing new ports, we'll adapt - though it would be nice if swift listened to the old default and the new default for a release.

It *sounds* like swift is saying there will be no default now at all, and deployers get to choose an arbitrary number as long as they register it with keystone? Thats fine too - but it would be good to have a deprecation period so folk can adjust without panic. 

Actually I wanted to ask what Swift folk think of having swift generally run behind apache/nginx/etc - I'm considering moving all our API services to be routed behind a single port so that firewall rules can be simpler, less SSL negotiation has to happen and so forth."}, {'account_id': 330, 'date': '2014-09-05 23:15:47.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

This is the deprecation step. We're keeping the recommended ports in the sample config file the same as the previous defaults as if they weren't specified. It is (and always was) expected that deployers will be using the sample configs as a guideline of what needs to be set and reasonable values to set it to.

This change allows us to take the next step of changing the recommended ports without breaking existing clusters, since they will have explicitly set the ports.

My plan/goal is to have this land in Juno and the change to recommended ports in Kilo."}, {'account_id': 4190, 'date': '2014-09-05 23:17:30.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

@John I'm a little confused: this will cause an error on existing clusters, no? Until folk set the setting.... so its no different to just changing the default: folk will get an error until they set the setting/"}, {'account_id': 4190, 'date': '2014-09-05 23:17:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

check experimental'}, {'account_id': 330, 'date': '2014-09-05 23:25:57.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

The main reason we can't just change the default (and why this patch isn't equivalent to that) is because the port numbers are also referenced in the deployed rings in Swift clusters. So the value chosen in the config file must match the value in the rings.

Every Swift deployer has already explicitly referenced port numbers in the rings. This change requires that same port to be explicit in the configs (and recommends the old default). Later, we'll recommend a different port so that SELinux and devstack don't get cranky about it. And since "later" all the clusters will have already explicitly referenced the port, then a change to the recommended port doesn't affect their clusters. If we went straight to a new default without first making it explicit, then all of the data in the cluster would immediately become unavailable.'}, {'account_id': 4190, 'date': '2014-09-06 00:12:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

So what I was asking was - can you instead migrate like this:

step 1: listen on *two* ports by default - the old and the new. This keeps the rings working. Log (once per process!) when requests are received on the old port.

step 2: After a release cycle, or however long seems reasonable, stop listening on the old port by default.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-09-06 00:41:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

commit_message:
make the bind_port config setting required

In a long-term effort to change the recommended ports for Swift,
the first step is to require the bind_port in config files. Later,
we can change the recommended setting.

Anyone currently explicitly setting the ports will not be affected.
Anyone not setting the ports will need to specify them to match their
rings.

DocImpact

Change-Id: Icca83a263acdd0afc9016424a3e9f8c15e944789

commit_message:
Add 'bash-completion' to 'ironic help' response

If you do 'ironic' or 'ironic help', it will show a list of subcommands.
This adds 'bash-completion' to that list.

The 'ironic bash-completion' subcommand lists all of the commands.
It won't include 'bash-completion' in this list, to be consistent with
nova's and keystone's bash-completion subcommand.

Change-Id: I7f2b76ad2885d9fe34dc91a97ee77984a21a27f4
Closes-Bug: #1304488

commit_message:
Include `fault.text` in the log error message.

Before, the error message in `error_msg` could be too generic. It is
possible to add the `fault.text` containing some more infomation to the
error message.

Change-Id: Ifa8fdc545a5f16d2a17fd83ac9b0f24176ae559e
Closes-Bug: #1367741

error as is idiomatic.

Fail if keystone auth is not possible

autorization occurs fail, instead of skiping test

If there is no glance image, also fail, not skip

commit_message:
Fail if keystone auth is not possible

If any errors during initial keystone
autorization occurs fail, instead of skiping test

If there is no glance image, also fail, not skip

Change-Id: If27f0e69d374f63d95b737eb78b6f47d1a9845a6

Because still many services, including MongoDB, are logging to standard log
destination we should rotate the logs more agressively. Moreover MongoDB in
version 2.4 cannot use LogFacility, so it's easier to fix it in logrotate than

commit_message:
Adds "/var/log/messages" to hourly log rotation

Because still many services, including MongoDB, are logging to standard log
destination we should rotate the logs more agressively. Moreover MongoDB in
version 2.4 cannot use LogFacility, so it's easier to fix it in logrotate than
in MonngoDB module itself.

Change-Id: Ice1bbf4a3bf2d453a41d7660b8742a074ec29216
Closes-Bug: 1367234

commit_message:
Fix regression in swift store functional test

Fix regression introduced by commit
63195aaa3b12e56ae787598e001ac44d62e52865.  The commit populated a
singleton in glance.store.swift at import time to hold the swift
configuration.  The functional test, however, relies on tweaking
the config after importing the glance.store.swift module.

Change-Id: I5550dd591bcf0c62071635506780be51d560d597

commit_message:
Revert "Repair pysqlite transaction support"

This reverts commit 78fd290a89545de31e5c13f3085df23368a8afaa.

Unfortunally, this commit breaks unittests in Nova, Neutron and
Keystone. It's would be nice to adopt these projects, but it seems
to be, that we will do in in K release

Change-Id: Idf8ffa71fcd4aae476e1983762358f5087d370b3
Closes-Bug: #1367354

commit_message:
Fix constructed .drone.yml script line

"script" should be an array of commands. If it isn't,
the entry point is not executed.

Change-Id: I5bf0de26e8b8e62c65e401a5f2d98a2bc386abac

commit_message:
Added simple samples that exercise autoscaling

Added trivial templates that can be used to exercise basic
scaling group functionality: the mechanics of the scaling
actions.  These examples are deliberately spare, to
minimize dependencies.

Change-Id: Iddd63acc629d617f861215c12e20d250c53edd11
Partial-Bug: 1305425

commit_message:
Removed direct access to MessagingServer

Factory method provided by the library should be used to create a server
object. This allows to change servers internal implementation without
touching end users.

Also removed custom dispatcher. Its only purpose was to log messages.
If logging is configured accordingly all incoming messages will be
logged from oslo/messaging/_drivers/amqpdriver.py [1]

[1] http://goo.gl/nV9tcu

Closes-Bug: #1357236

Change-Id: Ic208994c5a64fd48528cb41d30a975d68d84af05

commit_message:
libvirt: start lxc from block device

Currently, lxc containers can be started only from an image.
Adding support to start lxc containers from block device volumes.

Separating the lxc disk handling code from _create_domain to _lxc_disk_handler
that will use block_device_mapping and will handle the pre and post lxc start
actions on the disk, both for images and volumes.

Implements blueprint libvirt-start-lxc-from-block-devices
Change-Id: Ia980f65384af2818f46d2e91df46f131b2ce3a77

This breaks TripleO. Basically all SSH commands in the TripleO CI is whitelisted[1]. The way to fix it would be to submit a new patch to that project adding the new SSH command line, but to that to take effect it would require the TripleO CI test environment to be rebuilt.

So as this patch is not fixing anything very important, I'm fine with reverting it now and then we can work on the CI first and then re-merge it.

commit_message:
Revert "Search line with awk itself and avoid grep"

This commit causes all tripleo ironic CI jobs to fail CI.
The tripleo test env's need to be adjusted and redeployed first
in order to accept a new command over ssh.

Change-Id: Id057603717777777536f7ca947792862724b28f5

commit_message:
Fix broken www-authenticate functional test

testQuotedWWWAuthenticateHeader functional test started failing
due to a change to keystonemiddleware.auth_token, which now adds
its own www-authenticate header in addition to the one that swift
keystoneauth adds.

This patch changes the functional test to check expected
swift generated header value is in the concatenation of
www-authenticate values.

Verified that functional tests still pass using tempauth.

Closes-Bug: 1368048
Change-Id: I913af077df800a559d259c1622f286ad10eae9df

commit_message:
Fix exception that is not properly raised

This commit fixes an exception that was not properly raised, and
also makes the exception more relevant.

This also fixes an outstanding bug where, if the agent
was not associated with a node, get_node_uuid() would fail in an
unexpected manner.

Change-Id: Ifca474a73dd50b5fd2242e5b7e938a5db04f27a8

commit_message:
Ensure lock list isn't mutated while iterating

While iterating over the acquired lock list we
do not want the lock.release call to mutate the
list that we are currently iterating over. To fix
this just iterate over a copy instead so that the
lock.release can remove without issue.

Change-Id: I157331ca116b97e17d10854b5227ac7ee67fac57

[{'created': '2014-03-27 03:15:00.000000000', 'message': "Translate Unauthorized NeutronClientException to NovaException

Requests to Neutron can fail during authentication when the auth_token
passed from Nova to Neutron via the client expires and this results in a
500 error in the Nova response. Rather than fail with a 500 error we can
handle the Unauthorized exception from the client and translate it to a
more specific NovaException, NotAuthorized in this case.

Note that the NotAuthorized NovaException is currently setting it's code
to 403 which is not appropriate for an Unauthorized
NeutronClientException.

This patch only wraps the allocate/deallocate_for_instance methods but
can probably also be applied to more methods in the neutronv2 API.

Closes-Bug: #1298075

commit_message:
Translate Unauthorized NeutronClientException to NovaException

Requests to Neutron can fail during authentication when the auth_token
passed from Nova to Neutron via the client expires and this results in a
500 error in the Nova response. Rather than fail with a 500 error we can
handle the Unauthorized exception from the client and translate it to a
more specific NovaException, the new Unauthorized NovaException in this
case.

This patch only wraps the allocate/deallocate_for_instance methods but
can probably also be applied to more methods in the neutronv2 API.

Closes-Bug: #1298075

Change-Id: I00479b8e2fc04e995f6e0e90d3e24de8c939178c

commit_message:
Add hooks to workaround patching bugs

Add several pre and post patching hooks and tests
for them.

* Stop or migrate corosync services from controller node
  and return them after the deployment

* Stop openstack services and kill pids that was
  not stopped together with their children

* Remove openstack packages before deployment
  to prevent conflicts during the update and rollback

Change-Id: Icfc17308d955e55b5e5b31a9c17e0b6d13d8ba10
Closes-bug: #1364081
Closes-bug: #1365635
Closes-bug: #1364068
Co-Authored-By: Vladimir Sharshov <vsharshov@mirantis.com>
Co-Authored-By: Bogdan Dobrelya <bdobrelia@mirantis.com>
Co-Authored-By: Vladimir Kuklin <vkuklin@mirantis.com>

commit_message:
Add claims testing to VirtNUMAHostTopology class

This will allow us to use NUMA topology information from hosts and
instances when making resource claims for scheduling and migrating
instances.

This patch adds the VirtNUMALimitTopology class and corresponding
cells class that are used to represent the limits, and a method
claim_test() on the VirtNUMAHostTopology class that does the checking.

Blueprint: virt-driver-numa-placement
Change-Id: Ic21d559edf292e5b5dc1bba966e10ec4af0f706e

commit_message:
Add the ability to extract the query params from a urlsplit

The query params are quite useful to have (in collapsed or
non-collapsed modes) by applications that want to use urls
in situations where these params actually matter and are used
to do things like configure settings...

Change-Id: Iaf1b6a98f4152482d2f991b9dc7e4e24664c8b80

commit_message:
Getting deleted recordsets returns a 404

Getting recordsets of a deleted domain from the
v2 api now returns a domain_not_found exception
similar to v1

Change-Id: I3532ddd139f534b5ac77c1fdfdd7c4cc326e1f5c
Closes-Bug: 1367954

Remove templates from toctrees

We don't want the templates to show up in the RSS feed, so exclude them
from being converted to HTML and listed in the toctree.

- gate-rally-dsvm-keystone http://logs.openstack.org/40/120340/1/check/gate-rally-dsvm-keystone/477813e : SUCCESS in 17m 17s (non-voting)'}, {'account_id': 2903, 'date': '2014-09-10 15:05:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

(3 comments)

It looks like we should be adding options specifically for the memcache token backend. The KVS arguments cannot be applies to all KVS systems (this would mean that you cannot configure one kvs system independent of others).

I would focus on getting the options added specifically for the memcached token backend.

The [memcache]/servers option will allow for configuring multiple urls, perhaps it is best to add more options to the memcached config section.'}, {'account_id': 708, 'date': '2014-09-10 17:39:50.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

(2 comments)

I don't think we can add enough options to [memcache] section to cover all possible arguments different backends can receive. I think passing just a parsed JSON object will allow more extensibility here."}, {'account_id': 2903, 'date': '2014-09-10 18:38:44.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I'm ok with the arguments for the pool to be global, e.g. any arguments to the memcache pool come from the memcache section.

But the json string will override any *other* arguments passed to the backends."}, {'account_id': 708, 'date': '2014-09-11 11:20:14.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

in favor of explicit config arguments in https://review.openstack.org/119452'}]

commit_message:
Replace "tenant" with "project" in visible strings

OpenStack Dashboard uses "Project" rather than "Tenant" throughout
the code base. Only a few string with "tenant" are remaining,
and this commit cleans them up.

This commit also replaces "Id/id" with "ID"
for consistency in visible strings.

Change-Id: I2908ea16eb2d4f27af1e9ad0d653d790fab2faae
Closes-Bug: #1366973

commit_message:
Marks mysql slave read-only

When a slave is attached to a master site, this change will
mark the slave site as read-only to prevent the slave site
from being updated by users.  Only users with root privileges
or slave priveleges will be able to update the database.

Change-Id: Idb6c54b85a23af9a468ff9d62b3110fa72ff7da0
Closes-bug: #1359392

commit_message:
Fix VMware Namespace capitalization & description

The namespace had incorrect capitalization. Also,
added additional text in description to make people
aware that the properties only apply to the VMware
compute driver.

Change-Id: Ic1c3c333a1c70782a0780ace0323b2f6728bdd09
Closes-bug: 1367548

[{'created': '2014-09-10 04:34:57.000000000', 'message': 'Fix CommonImageProperties missing ":"

The namespace had inconsistent naming when compared to
other namespaces.

OS::Glance:CommonImageProperties
 should be
OS::Glance::CommonImageProperties

Change-Id: Iea9860be66eb06250f8a53b8c44ab787e9c8082a
Closes-Bug: 1367545
'}]
commit_message:
Fix CommonImageProperties missing ":"

The namespace had inconsistent naming when compared to
other namespaces.

OS::Glance:CommonImageProperties
 should be
OS::Glance::CommonImageProperties

Change-Id: Iea9860be66eb06250f8a53b8c44ab787e9c8082a
Closes-Bug: 1367545

commit_message:
Add baremetal API tests about console

This patch set adds tests og below Ironic APIs:

* GET /v1/nodes/(node_uuid)/states/console
* PUT /v1/nodes/(node_uuid)/states/console

Partially Implements blueprint: missing-baremetal-api-test

Change-Id: I019534f970d7c7bae8ccc3799cfac48116c81510

commit_message:
Move response code checking to client for v3 identity tests

test_Create_update_delete_policy had  a call to get_policy where the
result was not used at all so I removed it.

Partially Implements blueprint: client-checks-success

Change-Id: I06718380aa337886908c06f8fb7312c5f0c89f6a

commit_message:
Search line with awk itself and avoid grep

In ssh driver, some command sets are needlessly long.
"awk" command can search line itself. This fixes it.

Change-Id: Ie900aebe2f9ff7745c0456c5650204df84d0e799
Closes-Bug: #1365268

Remove templates from toctrees

We don't want the templates to show up in the RSS feed, so exclude them
from being converted to HTML and listed in the toctree.

commit_message:
Make requests requirement !=2.4.0

There is a bug in requests 2.4.0 which causes the ec2 collector to fail.
Fixing this would require us digging below our requests abstraction so
electing to pin the requests version.

Upstream bug: https://github.com/kennethreitz/requests/issues/2192

Change-Id: I471463e3b82cfb6ba910ebf75cfbf5ecebb56b4e

commit_message:
Run pki init conditionally

Running pki initialization conditionally, run it by default
for backwards compatibility.

Change-Id: I42f839574309d4ba5dcbfe1482c6c41bf0cf6cd1

commit_message:
Fixed writers bugs when switching to RPC

Processors are now running forever, operations needs to be flushed as
file is not closed with every run.
Report file is now consistent between each run.

Change-Id: If8dbca2359920c5975892d919077453452043490

commit_message:
Log translation hint for Heat.tests

Currently, Log translation is motivated by oslo's move to prioritized
translation of strings, as documented at
https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/LoggingStandards#Log_Translation

- add log translation hints for warning, error and info levels
- move from LOG.warning to LOG.warn
- remove use of % as a string formatter, use the log functionality
  instead

Partial implements blueprint log-translation-hints

Change-Id: Ia961196df09d301b4c384ffe51413ffc5c15164e

commit_message:
Log translation hint for Heat.common

Currently, Log translation is motivated by oslo's move to prioritized
translation of strings, as documented at
https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/LoggingStandards#Log_Translation

- add log translation hints for warning, error and info levels
- move from LOG.warning to LOG.warn
- remove use of % as a string formatter, use the log functionality
  instead

Partial implements blueprint log-translation-hints

Change-Id: I715f69154bd199dabac7d537b982b875204f8b33

commit_message:
Fixed ZipFile not supporting backends

Opening ZipFile with a backend will result in corrupted archives if the
file is closed and opened multiple times.

Change-Id: Ia0e5f50f51f5157c245041b091eca38676f978df

commit_message:
Migrate security_groups_basic to tempest clients

Adds client argument to various helper methods, so methods would work in tenant
context. In these methods tenant_id is either an input or retrieved from
client's rest_client arguments
Argument tenant_id is kept for legacy reasons, but it's not needed. When
working with native clients, network_client used to be loaded with admin creds.
Since this is no longer the case, tenant_id is no longer required for most
cases, and can be deduced from client.

Change-Id: Iaaa6b3b8dde22e1dd4da604ab35211d75d0ae5c6
Partially-implements: bp:tempest-client-scenarios

commit_message:
Change pacemaker default no-quorum-policy to 'stop'

Currently we use 'ignore' policy which makes sense for 2-nodes
clusters. Setting 'stop' policy makes sure that resources are stopped
in affected cluster partition.

Change-Id: I73dd5670713d0b6f93482ee1d7a14bac7e68ce1f

commit_message:
Cherry pick Nova fix for extra_specs bug

Cherry pick a Nova fix that resolves a scheduling error due to
the fact that extra_specs data was being canonicalized in the
Ironic driver but not in the relevant Nova scheduler filters.

Also, removes the previous Ironic temprevert that is no
longer needed (the Ironic drivers now subclass the Nova ones).

Change-Id: I45f3e0401709435ccf96d69e1703a880d40b8660

commit_message:
Precompilation of expressions

- performance boost in case of precompilation about ~50 times
- no exceptions in case of missing keys if expression part
which is using the key is not evaluated

Change-Id: I3c883f390f1ebe886799bc0215e00a21647b127c

commit_message:
Use single quotes for db schema sanity check

double quotes would cause failure when mysql running on ANSI sql_mode.

Change-Id: I891b61035ecb90b91a9ccdbec14dd567c575299b
Closes-Bug:1365019

commit_message:
Avoid string concatenation in Volume Type Extra Spec Edit

We should avoid using string concatenation so that translators
can control the word order in their translations.

Change-Id: I7a717b15fc978eec4448caf0962e2ffacfaf7645
Closes-Bug: #1366481

commit_message:
Corrected AZ FilterAction and table filter

The Availability Zone table was using the Host Aggregates filter action
so that has been changed to use the correct filter action, and fixed
Availability Zone filter action accessing an attribute that did not exist.

Change-Id: Ib9daaaeffade0ee30115f47f065f9f86ec6eb70c
Closes-Bug: 1362850

commit_message:
Version independent plugins

A Framework for creating plugins that work across identity versions.
Upon creating a generic plugin the plugin will go and discover what
versions are available on the server and then attemp to construct a
suitable plugin.

Blueprint: version-independant-plugins
Change-Id: If7fed94aaf4636e80a9c3a834cf6c5430f20e489

The simplest way to test is:

1. Launch an instance with encrypted ephemeral storage
2. Create a test file in the instance with known text
3. Flush I/O cache in the instance with sync
4. Flush I/O cache on the host
5. Grep for the test file text in the instances ephemeral disk, i.e. grep <test text> /dev/<volume group>/<instance disk>; if grep returns no result the encryption works.

Note: the above device is different from the device specified in /data/nova/instances/<uu-id>/libvirt.xml or generally associated with the instance, since when encryption is enabled Nova interacts only with the other end of the dm-crypt pipe, which is located in /dev/mapper/.

Does this answer your question?'}, {'account_id': 7746, 'date': '2013-08-28 19:57:16.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 17:

The simplest way to test is:

1. Launch an instance with encrypted ephemeral storage 

2. Create a test file in the instance with known text 

3. Flush I/O cache in the instance with sync 

4. Flush I/O cache on the host 

5. Grep for the test file text in the instances ephemeral disk, i.e. grep <test text> /dev/<volume group>/<instance disk>; if grep returns no result the encryption works.

Note: the above device is different from the device specified in /data/nova/instances/<uu-id>/libvirt.xml or generally associated with the instance, since when encryption is enabled Nova interacts only with the other end of the dm-crypt pipe, which is located in /dev/mapper/.

As I mentioned in the inline comment, the ephemeral storage encryption can be tested with the mock key manager provided for testing purposes. Because specifics of the key manager are isolated behind the key manager interface, it is not necessary to have a fully implemented key manager to test the provided functionality.

"As I mentioned in the inline comment, the ephemeral storage encryption can be tested with the mock key manager provided for testing purposes. Because specifics of the key manager are isolated behind the key manager interface, it is not necessary to have a fully implemented key manager to test the provided functionality.
Work is on-going to integrate the key manager interface with either KMIP or (more likely) Barbican, however, I am not certain when this work will be completed."

While a full key manager it is not necessary to do basic testing, it is necessary to use this code in any sort of production environment. I don't like the idea of merging code in trunk that cannot be deployed. Previous patch broke unencrypted LVM snapshots because the initialization method for LVM imagebackend relied on instance object argument to determine whether encryption was being used. When the imagebackend was initialized for a snapshot, however, instance was not passed and defaulted to None, resulting in a get() call on a None type object.

In the new patch instance is always passed when an imagebackend object is created. This will also be handy when we will be implementing encrypted snapshots, which will require attaching the encryption key uuid to the snapshot.'}, {'account_id': 5652, 'date': '2014-02-14 20:25:41.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 70: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

[{'created': '2013-08-06 18:12:56.000000000', 'message': 'Adds ephemeral storage encryption

This patch add ephemeral storage encryption for LVM back-end instances.
Encryption is implemented by passing all data written to and read
from the logical volumes through a dm-crypt layer. Most instance
operations such as pause/continue, suspend/resume, reboot, etc. are
supported. Snapshots are also supported but are not encrypted at
present.

Implements: encryption of ephemeral storage
Change-Id: I871af4018f99ddfcc8408708bdaaf480088ac477
'}, {'created': '2013-08-07 13:08:47.000000000', 'message': 'Adds ephemeral storage encryption

This patch adds ephemeral storage encryption for LVM back-end instances.

operations such as pause/continue, suspend/resume, reboot, etc. are
supported. Snapshots are also supported but are not encrypted at
present.

When fully functional, the proposed code will provide data-at-rest
security for all ephemeral storage drives, preventing access to data
while the instance or compute host are shut down.

'}, {'created': '2013-09-11 20:30:00.000000000', 'message': 'Add ephemeral storage encryption for LVM back-end images

This patch adds ephemeral storage encryption for LVM back-end instances.
Encryption is implemented by passing all data written to and read from
the logical volumes through a dm-crypt layer. Most instance operations
such as pause/continue, suspend/resume, reboot, etc. are supported.
Snapshots are also supported but are not encrypted at present.

The proposed code provides data-at-rest security for all ephemeral
storage drives, preventing access to data while an instance is
shut down, or in case the compute host is shut down while an instance is
running.

Options controlling the encryption state, cipher and key size are
specified in the "ephemeral_storage_encryption" options group. The boolean
"enabled" option turn encryption on and off and the "cipher" and "key_size"
options specify the cipher and key size, respectively.

Note: depends on cryptsetup being installed.

Implements: blueprint encrypt-ephemeral-storage
Change-Id: I871af4018f99ddfcc8408708bdaaf480088ac477
docImpact
SecurityImpact

'}, {'created': '2014-02-27 19:29:32.000000000', 'message': 'Adds ephemeral storage encryption for LVM back-end images

This patch adds ephemeral storage encryption for LVM back-end instances.
Encryption is implemented by passing all data written to and read from
the logical volumes through a dm-crypt layer. Most instance operations
such as pause/continue, suspend/resume, reboot, etc. are supported.
Snapshots are also supported but are not encrypted at present. VM rescue
and migration are not supported at present.

The proposed code provides data-at-rest security for all ephemeral
storage disks, preventing access to data while an instance is
shut down, or in case the compute host is shut down while an instance is
running.

Options controlling the encryption state, cipher and key size are
specified in the "ephemeral_storage_encryption" options group. The boolean
"enabled" option turns encryption on and off and the "cipher" and "key_size"
options specify the cipher and key size, respectively.

Note: depends on cryptsetup being installed.

Implements: blueprint encrypt-ephemeral-storage
Change-Id: I871af4018f99ddfcc8408708bdaaf480088ac477
DocImpact
SecurityImpact

commit_message:
Adds ephemeral storage encryption for LVM back-end images

This patch adds ephemeral storage encryption for LVM back-end instances.
Encryption is implemented by passing all data written to and read from
the logical volumes through a dm-crypt layer. Most instance operations
such as pause/continue, suspend/resume, reboot, etc. are supported.
Snapshots are also supported but are not encrypted at present. VM rescue
and migration are not supported at present.

The proposed code provides data-at-rest security for all ephemeral
storage disks, preventing access to data while an instance is
shut down, or in case the compute host is shut down while an instance is
running.

Options controlling the encryption state, cipher and key size are
specified in the "ephemeral_storage_encryption" options group. The boolean
"enabled" option turns encryption on and off and the "cipher" and "key_size"
options specify the cipher and key size, respectively.

Note: depends on cryptsetup being installed.

Implements: blueprint lvm-ephemeral-storage-encryption
Change-Id: I871af4018f99ddfcc8408708bdaaf480088ac477
DocImpact
SecurityImpact

commit_message:
Allow out of quota failure status code to be 413 or 403

Due to HTTP response code changes for Bug 1298131, tempest skip
some cases to have jenkins pass. As nova change is merged now,
remove these skip tags. Also need to allow both HTTP413 and
HTTP403 because branchless Tempest needs to support both master and
icehouse/stable branches.

Change-Id: Iee392859a9fd1eec767cbf6292290d5b3ad7dcca
Related-Bug: #1298131

commit_message:
Template is not required on stack-adopt

stack-adopt does not require a template, so removing template
parameters passed to stack-adopt.

Change-Id: I713fba392b8b8bbebf2f0c9d9be220e5826bf993
Closes-Bug: #1300336

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-07-30 18:42:33.000000000', 'message': "Re-add keystone v3 auth with fixes

The first part of the commit is to re-propose the v3 auth changes.
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/92728/

The second part of the commit is to address the unexpected keyword
argument 'follow_redirect' and missing endpoint issue in certain
code path such as 'heat event-list' or 'heat resource-metadata'.
With the fix, follow_redirect argument is consumed by
SessionClient.  Heat endpoint is now passed from Heatclient
shell to SessionClient.

Unit tests were added and updated to cover the issue.

Change-Id: I0cdf837c924afe9cbd8826bdca5dd611c183efeb
Closes-Bug: #1349467
Closes-Bug: #1348297

commit_message:
Re-add keystone v3 auth with fixes

The first part of the commit is to re-propose the v3 auth changes.
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/92728/

The second part of the commit is to address the unexpected keyword
argument 'follow_redirect' and missing endpoint issue in certain
code path such as 'heat event-list' or 'heat resource-metadata'.
With the fix, follow_redirect argument is consumed by
SessionClient.  Heat endpoint is now passed from Heatclient
shell to SessionClient.

Unit tests were added and updated to cover the issue.

Change-Id: I0cdf837c924afe9cbd8826bdca5dd611c183efeb
Closes-Bug: #1349467
Closes-Bug: #1348297

@nikola, we really cannot knowingly break Ironic by merging this, even if it is only for a few days while waiting for corresponding ironic change to merge.  When Ironic breaks, this ripples out and breaks all CI for the Triple-O project which seriously impacts a large number of developers.

I am also concerned as to whether there might be something nasty lurking here, beyond simply the missing 'numa_topology' field for Ironic. Since the Ironic jenkins job fails every time this patch is posted, we've no way of knowing. 

It really is easy to avoid this - we just set a default value for 'numa_topology' if not already found."}, {'account_id': 1779, 'date': '2014-09-01 14:52:15.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 25.'}, {'account_id': 1779, 'date': '2014-09-01 14:53:37.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 25: Code-Review+2

commit_message:
Expose numa_topology to the resource tracker

This patch makes all the current drivers that implement
get_available_resource() return an additional 'numa_topology' field in
the resources dict. The libvirt driver will actually return useful data,
while other drivers only return 'None' at this time.

We also make the resource tracker check for the presence of this field.
The intent is that it be mandatory for all drivers to expose, but to
avoid breaking out of tree virt drivers, if the field is missing it
will be set to None.

Blueprint: virt-driver-numa-placement
Change-Id: I75e4aeea4636532cfd724f718e136fac5bb2d15e

commit_message:
Always add auth URI to unauthorized requests

For those services that use delay_auth_decision we need to support
adding the keystone URI rejection headers to the response in a uniform
way. I feel this should be more generic and that every 401 response
should contain this header.

Create a WSGI wrapper so that if a 401 is ever returned through
auth_token middleware we can add an additional WWW-Authenticate header.

Closes-Bug: #1349364
Change-Id: Ib5231a09fd5c6cb6cd17f07c87e982d2e8fde2bf

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-08-29 21:40:26.000000000', 'message': 'Add instance_extra_update_by_uuid() to DB API

Since we have multiple things reading from and writing to the
instance_extra table, we really need a way to just update the value
in a single column, by instance_uuid, without looking it up first,
without wiping the other columns, or updating them with stale data
introducing a race.

This adds the new API, updates instance_create() to pre-create the
extra record, and makes the numa_topology object do this sort of
update instead of creating the record itself.

NB: This includes changes to the numa topology stuff that I think
might need to be corrected in another patch, like removing
the instance_uuid parameter to the create() method. Also, with
instance pre-creating the record(s) for us, that should
potentially really be "save()".

Change-Id: I0819cab81467ab41551e8937be7443a7761cbfb8
'}, {'created': '2014-09-02 16:13:26.000000000', 'message': 'Add instance_extra_update_by_uuid() to DB API

commit_message:
Add instance_extra_update_by_uuid() to DB API

Since we have multiple things reading from and writing to the
instance_extra table, we really need a way to just update the value
in a single column, by instance_uuid, without looking it up first,
without wiping the other columns, or updating them with stale data
introducing a race.

This adds the new API, updates instance_create() to pre-create the
extra record, and makes the numa_topology object do this sort of
update instead of creating the record itself. As a result of this
change, we no longer need instance_extra_create() exposed out of
the DB API.

Change-Id: I0819cab81467ab41551e8937be7443a7761cbfb8

commit_message:
Add pci_requests to instance_extra table

Add a new text column, pci_requests, to the instance_extra table.
This column will be used to hold the data that is currently stored in
instance system_metadata.  The problem with its current location is
the 255 character limit, which becomes a more serious limitation with
the coming SR-IOV support.

Related to blueprint pci-passthrough-sriov

Change-Id: I84d02242c56ad56c597fe588407aaceb24910d0a

commit_message:
Add scheduler unit tests to enable bug fixes and refactoring

Improves the coverage for DVR scheduling and will allow safer bug
fixes and refactoring in follow-on patches.

Change-Id: I02d0126e31adcab88a7ee82ba1cb76f952c9a68c
Partial-bug: #1353266
Partial-bug: #1356639
Co-Authored-By: Swaminathan Vasudevan <swaminathan.vasudevan@hp.com>

[{'created': '2014-08-05 21:46:06.000000000', 'message': 'Fix AttributeError when setting external gateway on DVR router

DVR routers will have this manager initialized only after one
or more subnets have been attached to the router. To address
the issue, make sure the manager is defined and handle the snat
rules appropriately.

Change-Id: Ib46852f5b264e5ef2e2d499d3351f8974e393011
'}, {'created': '2014-08-06 01:51:37.000000000', 'message': 'Fix AttributeError when setting external gateway on DVR router

Currently the snat iptables manager is initialized only if one
or more subnets have been attached to the router (as snat ports
will be available then). However, if one attempts to set the
external gateway to the router before adding an interface, this
results into the exception observed.

To address the issue, make sure the dvr gateway interface (and
hence the centralized snat namespace with its iptables manager)
is initialized unconditionally. This allows the l3 agent to deal
with update requests for the router (external gw being set or
interfaces added) regardless of the order in which these requests
are made.

Closes-bug: #1353006

Change-Id: Ib46852f5b264e5ef2e2d499d3351f8974e393011

commit_message:
Fix AttributeError when setting external gateway on DVR router

DVR routers will have this manager initialized only after one
or more subnets have been attached to the router. To address
the issue, make sure the manager is defined and handle the snat
rules appropriately.

This patch also makes _update_arp_entry more defensive; this is
because the arp update process can be affected by the same issue:
the router may not have internal ports at the time the request
come in. This is likely when VM's port creation and router
configuration overlap slightly.

Closes-bug: #1353006

Change-Id: Ib46852f5b264e5ef2e2d499d3351f8974e393011
Co-authored-by: Rajeev Grover <rajeev.grover@hp.com>

commit_message:
Reset IPv6 detection flag after IPv6 tests

Resets a module level flag that was being left in the
state that the previous test set it to. This was causing
unrelated tests to fail if the last state was left disabled.

Closes-Bug: #1365829
Change-Id: Id3f6cb680f5d832e21966de7d4fa335c0c59697c

commit_message:
Stop having jsonutils place itself into anyjson

In order to avoid the case where libraries that use
taskflow (or vice-versa) pickup taskflows jsonutils
due to how jsonutils auto-registers with anyjson just
remove that registration process to begin with.

Since jsonutils is no longer being maintained we will
have to start patching these types of additions in
ourselves until/if we can use oslo.serialization as
a suitable replacement.

This mirrors the change in:

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/117844/

Change-Id: I5fe9e98f821fcd4e2904853de1a203141a6833f3

commit_message:
JSON Home data is required

For the initial implementation, the JSON Home data was optional. Now
that JSON Home is implemented, JSON Home data is required.

bp json-home

Change-Id: I5af70401fba892166cd107264e9d5eafe6bcbd03

Whilst the v2.Password plugin (which is used by default) will accept a

commit_message:
Always supply a username to auth_token tests setup

Whilst the v2.Password plugin (which is used by default) will accept a
None value for username this is incorrect behaviour. We should always
provide at least a username so that the plugin can do sensible error
handling if it is not present.

Change-Id: Id790b52f3b06240923f605754c7ffcf4ff136062
Closes-Bug: #1361444

commit_message:
Allow passing None for username in v2.Password

None must be an acceptable parameter for username in password due to
tests in other libraries, however we should still raise an error if
neither username or user_id is passed. Use and check a sentinel value
instead of None.

Change-Id: Id61cfd1423afa8f9dd964fda278f4fab40887512
Closes-Bug: #1361444

commit_message:
Returns 401 when unauthorized project access occurs

Throwing wsme based exceptions out of non-wsme context causes api server
to return 500 since the exception goes uncaught. Instead return
http response with error code 401 to return to client safely

Change-Id: Ifb753581e392ea7961b976bc97ee2348feb6825c
Closes-Bug: 1365770

commit_message:
Add new field micro_state to Volume table in Cinder db

As part of Cinder explicit state transition table work
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/110434/ alongwith the
transition table we will need to add a new field called
'micro_state' to the Cinder DB to keep the information
of the micro state in which the volume is present
currently. The current volume "status" can be combined
of multiple micro_state's which provides a finer
granularity and will help to maintain atomicity
guarantees.

Part of blueprint cinder-state-enforcer

Part of blueprint valid-states-api

Change-Id: I92aab0698bd8f6ff6065b6db30c528de2099465f

commit_message:
Run processes without screen

This introduces new run_process() and screen_service() functions and sets the
groundwork to change how DevStack starts services.  screen_service() is simply a
direct call to the screen portion of the old screen_it() function and is intended
to run commands that only need to run under screen, such as log file watchers.

run_process() is a replacement for screen_it() (which remains until all of the
services are updated).  The usage is similar but requires updates to every current
screen_it() call to remove everything that requires the command to be interpreted
by a shell.

The old run_process() and _run_process() functions are still present as
old_run_process() and _old_run_process() to support the deprecated screen_it()
function.  These will all go away in the future once all services have been
confirmed to have been changed over.

There is a similar new set of stop process functions stop_process() and
screen_stop_service().  The old screen_stop() will also remain for the deprecation
period.

As an initial test/demostration this review also includes the changes for
lib/cinder to demonstrate what is required for every service.

I included the scripts I used to test this; tests/fake-service.sh and
tests/run-process.sh are quite rough around the edges and may bite.  They should
mature into productive members of the testing ecosystem someday.

Change-Id: I03322bf0208353ebd267811735c66f13a516637b
