This change was unable to be automatically merged with the current state of the repository. Please rebase your change and upload a new patchset.'}, {'account_id': 5387, 'date': '2014-08-29 17:34:36.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 21:

(1 comment)

Running the container's processes as the host's root is a security concern. This patch allows the running of the container's processes as a non-root user from the context of the host. From the context of the container, it still appears to be root."}, {'account_id': 5387, 'date': '2014-08-29 17:38:06.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 22.'}, {'account_id': 7746, 'date': '2014-08-29 17:44:58.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 22: Code-Review+1

Is it up to the operator, then, to correctly configure the mapping so that it does not map to host root? I don't think I so anything in the code that would prevent that from happening."}, {'account_id': 5387, 'date': '2014-08-29 17:52:19.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 22:

Correct, it's up to the operator. It is also conceivable that an operator may want to leave containers running as root. For instance if an operator is only running a single tenant internal cloud, they may want to run privileged containers in order to run applications that cannot run in a user namespaced environment. On the other hand, running a public cloud with libvirt-lxc and user namespaces turned off would not be a good idea."}, {'account_id': 7746, 'date': '2014-08-29 17:54:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 22:

Do you think it may be worth logging a warning if the mapping is to host root?

What happens if name-spacing is turned off?'}, {'account_id': 5387, 'date': '2014-08-29 18:53:21.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 23.'}, {'account_id': 7368, 'date': '2014-08-29 19:00:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 23: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 5387, 'date': '2014-08-29 19:06:29.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 24.'}, {'account_id': 5387, 'date': '2014-08-29 19:09:26.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 24:

@Dan, I've added a log message when running without User Namespaces. When running Nova configured without User Namespaces, the containers it will spawn will be run as the host's root user. This is generally a bad idea, because the attack surface root has to break out of the container is considerably larger than any other user."}, {'account_id': 5387, 'date': '2014-08-29 19:13:16.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 25.'}, {'account_id': 7, 'date': '2014-08-29 19:13:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 24:

'}, {'created': '2014-05-22 16:21:23.000000000', 'message': "Add user namespace support for libvirt-lxc

This change adds two config values that allow deployers
to enable user namespacing for libvirt-lxc containers.
User namespacing allows the mapping of uids and gids in
a container to separate uids and gids outside of the
container. The main advantage of this is to allow a
container's processes to appear to be running as root,
while actually running as a different user on the host.

Implements: bp libvirt-lxc-user-namespaces

Change-Id: I5f517f228b477f8238eccbb604b9ffd0ebaa5927

"}, {'created': '2014-05-23 21:55:40.000000000', 'message': "Add user namespace support for libvirt-lxc

This change adds two config values that allow deployers
to enable user namespacing for libvirt-lxc containers.
User namespacing allows the mapping of uids and gids in
a container to separate uids and gids outside of the
container. The main advantage of this is to allow a
container's processes to appear to be running as root,

commit_message:
Add user namespace support for libvirt-lxc

This change adds two config values that allow deployers
to enable user namespacing for libvirt-lxc containers.
User namespacing allows the mapping of uids and gids in
a container to separate uids and gids outside of the
container. The main advantage of this is to allow a
container's processes to appear to be running as root,
while actually running as a different user on the host.

Implements: bp libvirt-lxc-user-namespaces

DocImpact: This adds two config options to the libvirt
group, uid_maps and gid_maps. Default values are empty
strings and will leave user namespacing disabled for
libvirt-lxc containers.

Change-Id: I5f517f228b477f8238eccbb604b9ffd0ebaa5927

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-06-06 08:00:59.000000000', 'message': 'VMware: spawn refactor - image handling

From examining the exist vmops spawn() coder, as-yet unmerged patches
undergoing review that impacts it, as well as anticipating additional
changes proposed in blueprints, it is apparent that the high branching
factor is a result of inefficient attempts to address various
permutations of the following:

- different types image to spawn with (sparse, flat, iso,
  streamOptimized, ova, ...)
- different ways to obtain the image (http download, datastore copy,
  direct use, ...)
- different ways to prepare the downloaded image bits into a usable
  image in the image cache (replace -flat.vmdk extent, convert from
  sparse, pick from imported VM, ...)
- different ways to employed the image that has made available (fully
  copy, as base of COW disk, direct use, ...)

This patch attempts to tease apart into three main areas of
responsibilites:

- ImageHandler classes : for obtaining bits of various kinds of images
- ImageProcessor classes : for processing the bits into a usable form to
                           be cached in the iamge cache
- Image user callbacks : for dealing with using a prepared/cached image
                         in a VM in various ways.

The hope is that this will allow for more self-contained additions/changes
to behaviors in these areas, as well as more avenues to test different
aspects of the spawn operation in isolation.

TODO:
Try to break this further into a few smaller patches, add a couple
more tests.

partial blueprint vmware-spawn-refactor

to behaviors in these areas in the future.

commit_message:
VMware: spawn refactor image fetch/cache

To more cleanly support the various permutations of the following during
spawn():
- different types image to spawn with (sparse, flat, iso,
  and streamOptimized, ova in the futre)
- different ways to obtain the image (http download, and direct
  datastore copy in the future)
- different ways to prepare the downloaded image bits into a usable
  image in the image cache (replace -flat.vmdk extent, convert from
  sparse, pick from imported VM, ...)

The following are introduced:
- Image prepare/fetch/cache functions : these are callbacks for
  processing the bits into a usable form to be cached in the image cache
  under various scenarios.
- Image fetching functions : these are callbacks called by the processor
  to obtain the bits for the hypervisor.

All unit tests should pass unmodified after this refactor.

This should will allow for more self-contained additions/changes
to behaviors in these areas in the future.

Co-authored-by: Radoslav Gerganov <rgerganov@vmware.com>

(11 comments)

Nice work Aaron.  The -1 is for some missed copy/paste typos and the help text.

I do have some general suggestions based on what OSC does:

* We've avoided plural forms in all commands in OSC even when they are a bit awkward in English.

* Any copyright statements that you retain with "OpenStack., LLC."  should be changed to "OpenStack Foundation".  It's up to you if files that were copied and modified are sufficiently different or not that the original copyright still holds.  The question of whether they are generally required is open to debate[0].

* You have mixed indention forms.  OSC generally uses hanging indents as in http://legacy.python.org/dev/peps/pep-0008/#indentation.  I prefer the closing paren on its own line and indented to align with the original statement.  But being consistent is part of OSC's guiding philosophy.


[0] From non-binding opinions from more than one lawyer that don't represent any of us on the openstack-legal list and others places, copyright statements don't have much value in this environment, it is the license that is important.  $EMPLOYER often sees things differently though.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-09-04 00:01:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8: Verified-1

commit_message:
Initial congressclient

This patch adds client support for congress with keystone and supports
the following api commands:

	$ openstack congress policy list
	$ openstack congress policy row get
	$ openstack congress policy rule create
	$ openstack congress policy rule delete
	$ openstack congress policy rules list

Change-Id: I624b54f6cf2614eaec970c8bdd3766291dcc9489

commit_message:
Fix security group list when not defined for an instance

If an instance has an empty security group list an exception
is thrown due to iteration attempt of None.

To fix this, this patch modifies get_instance_security_group
to return an empty list instead of None.

Conflicts:
	nova/tests/api/openstack/compute/contrib/test_neutron_security_groups.py
	nova/tests/network/security_group/test_neutron_driver.py

Change-Id: I7efb3c3a58d7e20501d126c6d194479ca1d14166
Closes-Bug: #1291489
(cherry picked from commit c32986966dfd034c3d706b2e9ab2820a2c3cfc3e)

I don't think there's an argument here about number of places touched in the Cinder code."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-09-10 16:55:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+1

Build succeeded.

- gate-cinder-pep8 http://logs.openstack.org/55/120455/1/check/gate-cinder-pep8/ec3d2e1 : SUCCESS in 5m 22s

- check-tempest-dsvm-postgres-full http://logs.openstack.org/55/120455/1/check/check-tempest-dsvm-postgres-full/9bfa6b1 : SUCCESS in 1h 00m 01s
- check-tempest-dsvm-neutron-full http://logs.openstack.org/55/120455/1/check/check-tempest-dsvm-neutron-full/56134b9 : SUCCESS in 51m 07s
- check-tempest-dsvm-neutron-heat-slow http://logs.openstack.org/55/120455/1/check/check-tempest-dsvm-neutron-heat-slow/997282d : SUCCESS in 18m 18s
- check-grenade-dsvm http://logs.openstack.org/55/120455/1/check/check-grenade-dsvm/7739a90 : SUCCESS in 46m 41s
- gate-cinder-pylint http://logs.openstack.org/55/120455/1/check/gate-cinder-pylint/ff78aeb : SUCCESS in 9m 14s
- check-devstack-dsvm-cells http://logs.openstack.org/55/120455/1/check/check-devstack-dsvm-cells/19ac652 : SUCCESS in 13m 37s
- gate-rally-dsvm-cinder http://logs.openstack.org/55/120455/1/check/gate-rally-dsvm-cinder/5861fe7 : SUCCESS in 16m 47s (non-voting)'}, {'account_id': 6172, 'date': '2014-09-10 21:43:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Walter, Eric


OK let me describe this from very begging. With all possible solutions, and why keeping it in requirements is best one. 


1) (osprofiler optimal) Put a lot of try/finally and if condtions

If Osprofiler is optional we are not able to use with "profile.Trace()", and decortas "profiler.trace_cls()" and "profiler.trace()".
And we will need to put a lot of  "try/finally/if" stuff in code, which will make reading code really hard. 
To understand how bad it will be take a look at this gist:
 https://gist.github.com/boris-42/e5ffbe1077e4f8f3da09

We are expecting to have a lot of profiling "points" in code, so in such case we will produce real mess (mixing business logic and profiling is really bad practice) 


2) (osprofiler optimal) Create a fake cinder.utils.profiler that will have similiar API to osprofiler. 
And if osprofiler is presented it will use it, if not nothing will happen. 

This makes code very clean (like in case of osprofiler in requirements). 
But it produce a lot of issues. As we all know OpenStack is not only Cinder (there are > 10 projects, that will have osprofiler).
So we will need to repeat this code in 10 places.
Such kind of copy pasting is very bad, that's why people create oslo-incubator, but experience from oslo-incubator, showed that it is still
bad to copy-paste code even if this operation is automated. So currently everything from oslo-incubator is moving to separated lib, wich means
that fake osprofiler api will be moved to separated lib. So we are coming back to adding one more dependency in requirements.  


3) (osprofiler in requirments). Everything works out of box, easy to use, easy to maintain, unified across different projects'}, {'account_id': 4523, 'date': '2014-09-10 22:05:43.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I like option #2 and don't understand the argument against it there at all, but it's a moot point because in the Cinder IRC meeting today it was decided to stick with the status quo for reasons that aren't about the implementation itself."}, {'account_id': 4523, 'date': '2014-09-10 22:05:47.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned'}, {'account_id': 6172, 'date': '2014-09-10 22:10:38.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Eric,

Approach 1 is probably good enough, in case of 1 single project.

But when you need to have N copies of same code in more then 10 projects and maintain them, it makes things really complex and bad. That is actually why such thing like "libs" were invented. (to avoid copy pasting)'}]

commit_message:
Make osprofiler library optional for services

This makes it possible to run Cinder w/o osprofiler
installed.  Note that you may need to remove it from
your api-paste configuration as well.

It remains in requirements.txt since the default
api-paste configuration does use it.

Closes-Bug: #1361239

Change-Id: I46199f6e951c02a80e9cc763de364dbbd800b10d

commit_message:
Log ERROR power state in node_power_action()

Power driver can returns ERROR state. Log this error and do not
break requested action (this can be unknown valid state).

Partial-Bug: #1358816
Change-Id: I9b26440671cb44b58016dfd796adbd8fedd483ae

commit_message:
Translator functions cleanup part 3

This part fixes ironic/conductor, ironic/dhcp and ironic/objects
folders.

Some modules use _ function for log translation, even when the
translated string is passed to e.g. LOG.warn function. This patch
fixes it, using translator functions appropriate for corresponding
log levels. Translator functions, imported from
ironic.openstack.common.gettextutils are now imported from
ironic.common.i18n. Translator functions are imported the same way
across all modules. All places that are changed conform to
http://docs.openstack.org/developer/oslo.i18n/guidelines.html

Partial-bug: #1364813

Change-Id: Ib4b93cc49f16836a95c7cfb4c5f1705f5cbbb31f

commit_message:
Make assertion in assert_ostf_run_certain more verbose

Right now if assert_ostf_run_certain fails, the output is
"AssertionError: Condition was False."
which does not help much. The change makes it more verbose
giving the details of tests which must have passed but failed.

Change-Id: Iab373c3d4809e6f27147f9331f80ba03f02ae801

commit_message:
Install the correct arping package for neutron

Debian requires the iputils-arping package (not arping)
for the neutron L3 agent.

Co-Authored-By: Dan Prince <dprince@redhat.com>

Change-Id: I2b127a247852fd5c6b9b2d270ba13f012386fe31
Closes-Bug: #1352558

commit_message:
Change default congress port to non reserved port number 1789

This patch changes the default port number congress-server uses from 8080
to 1789 which is not reserved by anyone yet. 1789 is also the date that
the United States Congress was created so this number seems like a good
fit.

Change-Id: Ie3cf2639408cf3aa8d2cb64532871835f1cdf0d1
Closes-bug: 1364126

commit_message:
Use mock from unittests where possible

To ensure that we work with python 3.4 (the mock library
that is not built-in to the standard library appears
currently broken there) we should try to use the mock
that is built-in to python 3.3+ when possible to ensure
maximum compatibility.

Change-Id: Ifc2fcb9f52ffc24166857492579a84539bcdf071

subject: Correct api return code for invalid urls
messages:
[{'account_id': 4395, 'date': '2014-09-05 19:58:29.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 4395, 'date': '2014-09-05 20:03:56.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 9253, 'date': '2014-09-05 20:09:15.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

In my not-so-humble opinion, 404 is an incorrect response for methods that aren't implemented by the server.  By the HTTP RFC, it should be 501 when the method isn't supported, and 405 if the method is understood, but it doesn't apply to the specified resource.

404 make sense when communicating that a resource that is part of a collection isn't there (e.g. was deleted.)  A path that will *never* work is conceptually different, and that difference should be communicated to the caller.

A cursory google search yielded the following doc which does a pretty good job of explaining this: http://apiux.com/2013/03/28/2-steps-api-error-codes/"}, {'account_id': 9253, 'date': '2014-09-05 20:16:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

commit_message:
Correct api return code for invalid urls

This patch changes the server response from 501 to 404 when a request
is made to a url that is unknown. This behavior makes the behavior in
congress also consistent with how the other openstack apis function.

Change-Id: I537aa3a9b8229fbeea5fba4dcb1a8c7e905bf7d3
Closes-bug: 1366177

commit_message:
Remove unneed step to set fixed-ip and neutron cleanup

This patch removes an uneeded step to set a fixed ip on a port. This is
unneeded because neutron automatically allocates you a fixed-ip when
the port is created. In addition, this hides the provider information which is
only shown if one configures neutron to use vxlan/vlan for the transport type.

Change-Id: Id08d456cac0dcbf9b8517779ebaccfd5d9025bef

(5 comments)

I think there are enough comments/questions on this that it warrants a -1 for now.

I'm specifically concerned about the duplicate error handling required for sqla exceptions like IntegrityError, DataError, ProgrammingError and OperationalError (basically most of the sqla exceptions we handle).  I'd at least like an explanation of the need for this in the commit message and whether or not this is just a short-term thing until oslo.db abstracts this for us or if it's permanent, because if that's the case it's going to be hard to maintain, i.e. devs and reviewers will need to remember to handle multiple types of exceptions now.

The oslo.utils/timeutils thing could probably also be mentioned in the commit message since it's tripped a few people up while reviewing this and the TODO comments in the code aren't making it clear enough.

Overall I think most of this is minor though and shouldn't hold us up from getting this into Juno.  If the exception handling is for some specific reason then I'm going to need to do another pass on the nova code to see if anything was missed."}, {'account_id': 1849, 'date': '2014-09-03 00:46:47.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 38: -Code-Review

would like to see matt's questions answered"}, {'account_id': 6849, 'date': '2014-09-03 08:18:03.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 38:

(1 comment)

As an oslo.db maintainer I can provide a bit more info on why we need to catch additional exceptions here. Eugeniya/Andrey, please mention this in the commit message.

Common DB code always meant to wrap SQLAlchemy exceptions to be able to handle them (e.g. to retry methods on deadlock). The way it was implemented (decorators on Session methods) didn't actually allow us to wrap *all* exceptions, but only a subset of them. We recently changed that by doing wrapping at the lower level within SQLAlchemy. This gave us the ability to wrap all possible DB exceptions. So we kind of fixed the old annoying bug. As a drawback, we found out, that code in the consuming projects often doesn't expect us to wrap some exceptions, i.e. has workarounds for that bug (e.g. IntegrityError when SQLAlchemy Code is used instead of ORM), so the 'raw' SQLAlchemy IntegrityError/OperationalError is expected instead of DBDuplicateEntry/DBError. To make the transition between different versions of openstack/common/db code as well as older and newer releases of oslo.db smooth we propose that we *temporarily* handle both exceptions here and remove the old exceptions later in a few releases of oslo.db"}, {'account_id': 6849, 'date': '2014-09-03 11:19:18.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 38:

btw, this will effectively fix https://bugs.launchpad.net/nova/+bug/1353131 (it fails because we *didn't* wrap exceptions raised in Query.all() calls before)"}, {'account_id': 9545, 'date': '2014-09-03 12:37:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 38:

'}, {'created': '2014-09-03 13:45:53.000000000', 'message': "Move to oslo.db

Replace common oslo code nova.openstack.common.db by usage
of oslo.db library and remove common code.

Also added catches of oslo.db exceptions(such as DBError,
DBDuplicateEntry, etc). This was made because of recent changes in oslo.db
which doing wrapping of exceptions at the lower level within SQLAlchemy.
This gave the ability to wrap all possible DB exceptions.
But code in the consuming projects often doesn't expect oslo.db to wrap some
exceptions so the 'raw' SQLAlchemy IntegrityError/OperationalError is expected
instead of DBDuplicateEntry/DBError. To make the transition between different
versions of openstack/common/db code as well as older and newer releases
of oslo.db smooth we propose that we *temporarily* handle both exceptions
here and remove the old exceptions later in a few releases of oslo.db

Co-Authored-By: Eugeniya Kudryashova  <ekudryashova@mirantis.com>

Closes-Bug: #1353131
Change-Id: I0649539e071b2318ec85ed5d70259c949408e64b

commit_message:
Move to oslo.db

Replace common oslo code nova.openstack.common.db by usage
of oslo.db library and remove common code.

Replaced catching of raw sqlalchemy exceptions by catches
of oslo.db exceptions(such as DBError, DBDuplicateEntry, etc).

Co-Authored-By: Eugeniya Kudryashova  <ekudryashova@mirantis.com>

Closes-Bug: #1364986
Closes-Bug: #1353131
Closes-Bug: #1283987
Closes-Bug: #1274523
Change-Id: I0649539e071b2318ec85ed5d70259c949408e64b

commit_message:
Proxy Nova baremetal commands to Ironic

This patch changes the Nova Baremetal baremetal_nodes.py file so that
node-list and node-show commands are proxied to ironic.

This is an initial draft.

[{'created': '2014-09-04 13:11:17.000000000', 'message': "Fixes Cinder fails to upload volume to vhd image

The method copy_volume_to_image from windows.py specifies the
wrong volume format, namely 'vpc'. In this case, the upload_volume
method from image_utils will attempt to convert the volume to vhd
which will result in an error from qemu as it does not recognize
the format.

This patch fixes this issue by using 'vhd' as a format when
uploading volumes

Change-Id: Ifa675316e19f9a795e103fd56fcdf4e3ed00aab7
Closes-Bug: #1365487
"}]
commit_message:
Fixes Cinder fails to upload volume to vhd image

The method copy_volume_to_image from windows.py specifies the
wrong volume format, namely 'vpc'. In this case, the upload_volume
method from image_utils will attempt to convert the volume to vhd
which will result in an error from qemu as it does not recognize
the format.

This patch fixes this issue by using 'vhd' as a format when
uploading volumes

Change-Id: Ifa675316e19f9a795e103fd56fcdf4e3ed00aab7
Closes-Bug: #1365487

commit_message:
Adding HTTP mode to HAProxy stats

HAProxy's stats interface was not launching due to the default mode
for HAProxy having been set to TCP.  This patch remedies this by
directlys setting the http mode on the listener.

Change-Id: I367473049a52bf3ca0b2ac482ddb96ee39d6e045
Closes-Bug: #1355763

[{'created': '2014-09-09 18:04:04.000000000', 'message': 'Support py34 tox target.

OpenStack is making a push to move projects that had been tested on py33
to py34 because py34 will have a much larger install base (and is
consequently easier to test).

The python 3.4 json lib returns new and different error strings when
json decoding fails. Remove assertions from test_load_list_from_json
hat check these error strings, instead simply rely on assertRaises to
assert that the appropriate error is thrown.

Change-Id: Ia6603783014b0114de0f29664834d21196744774
'}]
commit_message:
Support py34 tox target.

OpenStack is making a push to move projects that had been tested on py33
to py34 because py34 will have a much larger install base (and is
consequently easier to test).

The python 3.4 json lib returns new and different error strings when
json decoding fails. Remove assertions from test_load_list_from_json
hat check these error strings, instead simply rely on assertRaises to
assert that the appropriate error is thrown.

Change-Id: Ia6603783014b0114de0f29664834d21196744774

commit_message:
Fix directory value for compile_catalog

Commit 7a192987c0a5edb9e239ffb4aba3b1dac083b41e sets
up swift for translation but the compile_catalog
directory option is pointing at the wrong location
to scan for po files.

Change-Id: Id4dd24ddfde735ef8ef064882bea045361b5db90
Closes-Bug: #1367086

Our pxe_ipminative driver also supports sending notifications to Ceilometer.

Cheers,

commit_message:
Deprecate Ironic compute driver and sched manager

Updates the Ironic compute driver and scheduler manager so that they
subclass the now in-Nova-tree driver classes. This should de-duplicate
code maintenance across Nova and Ironic and also provide end users
an easier upgrade path (with Deprecation log messages).

This patch also removes the old Ironic compute driver tests and classes
since those now live in Nova.

This patch also removes a line from tox.ini which was copying the second
set of unit test outputs; those no longer exist, since we are no longer
running unit tests on nova code in this tree.

Co-Authored-By: Dan Prince <dprince@redhat.com>
Co-Authored-By: Devananda van der Veen <devananda.vdv@gmail.com>

Change-Id: Ic194f779eca470e4a4dd8a3fbd31ca5a6f6b4f7e

commit_message:
Source lib/dstat in unstack.sh

`stop_dstat` function was extracted into $TOP_DIR/lib/dstat in commit
e0b08d04ab41f9aca96997c87bd9fa13feba2536 but the new lib was not sourced in
unstack.sh.

Change-Id: I6878552d9f384fdd7882e52000b37ac6a60844c3
Closes-Bug: 1366713

commit_message:
Fix column headings regression due to switch to cliutils

After switch to cliutils in https://review.openstack.org/72418
field_labels argument is no longer respected in print_list.
This patch updates cliutils to version introduced in
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/113978 and fixes usage
of the newly-introduced field_labels argument to print_list.

Change-Id: I4c5ca149816e4476f170b30de6855dec747522dd
Closes-Bug: #1342391

commit_message:
Add value for 'sed -i' parameter

Some versions of sed (MacOS and maybe BSD) show error if value for '-i'
parameter is missed. Without this change we can not run
'make version-yaml' on these OSes.

Change-Id: Ib81befbe302c9cb25c4bf67e45ae5dd90d58009a

commit_message:
Optimizes the functional test for IptablesManager

Limits ping timeout to 1 second instead of default 2*RTT.
Execution time is reduced from 18 seconds to 9 seconds.

Partial-bug: #1243216

commit_message:
Add PrePatching hook

- add prenode hook
- add prepatching node hook
- add tests

Remove some of packages before patching or rollback.

Change-Id: Id902df479afbce7de08ba7b271430a6013782ec5
Closes-bug: #1364068
Co-Authored-By: Vladimir Sharshov <vsharshov@mirantis.com>

commit_message:
Add PrePatching hook for HA envs

Add PrePatching and PostPathing hook for HA envs
that migrates pacemaker services
from the controllers being patched, process and
unbans particular nodes for OpenStack pacemaker
services.

Also:
- add post node deploy hook;
- rename PostDeploy to PostDeployment hook;
- refactroning hooks;
- add tests.

Change-Id: If1f3bba164c88710d2ae111ae813be0ae0f97803
Partial-bug: #1364068
Closes-bug: #1365635
Co-Authored-By: Vladimir Sharshov <vsharshov@mirantis.com>

commit_message:
Add stop all OST services pre-deploy hook

For given (hook hardcode) services,
* 1st try to stop specified services
  gracefully with stop action
* 2nd, if there are some services' related processes
  are still running, send SIGKILL for all their childs as well.
* Add unit test with hardcode services list

Also change order of pre hooks:
1. PrePatchingHa
2. StopOSTServices
3. PrePatching

All of this now PreNode hooks.

Related-bug: #1364068

Change-Id: Ida1eb0fbedbd93c2898142205a09c6ee351eeac4
Signed-off-by: Bogdan Dobrelya <bdobrelia@mirantis.com>
Co-Authored-By: Dmitry Ilyin <dilyin@mirantis.com>

We already have `rally-manage tempest` with `install` subcommand, so I prefer to create `rally-manage tempest set-config`,which will replace generated file with specified by user.

commit_message:
Allow user specified tempest config file

* Now, "rally verify start --tempest-config" allows users to specify their
   tempest config file instead of rally autoconfiguring tempest

Change-Id: I0aebe67d027648b007ff5ca8acf45f0e8e076208
Closes-Bug: #1366733

Improve visual separation of entries.

Add some extra padding and a red (#BC1518) border to the bottom of each
entry to provide better visual separation.

commit_message:
Optionally use public DNS for unittest and build.

This commit adds an option to worker, use_public_dns,
so the containers used during unittest and build use 8.8.8.8
and 8.8.4.4 instead of their host's resolv.conf settings.

Change-Id: I8d272509d685eadce2cc2783699ca893b9901202

commit_message:
utilize drone cli to run unit tests when installed

if drone is installed we will use drone cli to run tests rather
than building our own dockerfile etc.   If .drone.yml exists
in the user's repo then we will use that natively, if not then
we will construct one via details in the planfile.

if drone is not installed, then we'll do the testing the old
fashioned way.

Created a new local.conf variable 'SOLUM_INSTALL_DRONE' which
will install drone during stack creation if set.

Change-Id: I528929df53561e9977d1b672e4b4ed0de4a89951

commit_message:
requests module plugged

What is done:
* urllib2 code changed to corresponding from requests
* error handling for APIclient updated in order to exploit requests
  exceptions classes.

Partially implements: blueprint refactoring-for-fuelclient

Change-Id: I7f1c0b390828f4a77daeaca370cfb16a5df3839d

subject: clone repo locally and then perform tests by doing a docker build.
messages:
[{'account_id': 7858, 'date': '2014-09-09 18:21:30.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 2506, 'date': '2014-09-09 19:19:20.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

What is advantage of doing 'docker build' over 'docker run'?

FWIW, docker build requires creation of the Dockerfile which is not required for 'docker run'."}, {'account_id': 7858, 'date': '2014-09-09 20:21:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

docker build gives us a few advantages.

1. we can add extra content a lot easier ( such as private keys )
2. we can set the WORKDIR for a consistant starting point of the tests
3. allows us to do the git clone outside of the container, so in theory we could run parallel jobs over it without recloning multiple times.'}, {'account_id': 7858, 'date': '2014-09-09 20:22:56.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 2506, 'date': '2014-09-09 20:39:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+2'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-09-09 23:37:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified+1

1) Suggestion requires interface changes, not related to driver itself.

[{'created': '2014-08-19 14:08:39.000000000', 'message': "Fix update of backend details in cmode driver

There are dependency on backend details, that are stored in database,
in cmode driver. And if share server could not be created for some reason,
backend details won't be present in database. This fix updates database
at start of server creation, before sending request for creation.
There are still present possibility to get empty details, but it is
not related to driver itself, it is related to gap between creation of server
in database and call of driver's method for server creation. That could be,
for example, in case when share-network provided with wrong network data.

also added unittests to changed method due to absense of it.

Change-Id: Id1f8a4607b0dd09eb79b56b600088e8a70fbd47a
Closes-Bug: #1357273

commit_message:
Fix update of backend details in cmode driver

There are dependency on backend details, that are stored in database,
in cmode driver. And if share server could not be created for some reason,
backend details won't be present in database. This fix updates database
at start of server creation, before sending request for creation.
There are still present possibility to get empty details, but it is
not related to driver itself, it is related to gap between creation of server
in database and call of driver's method for server creation. That could be,
for example, in case when share-network provided with wrong network data.

also added unittests to changed method due to absense of it.

Change-Id: Id1f8a4607b0dd09eb79b56b600088e8a70fbd47a
Closes-Bug: #1357273

commit_message:
Move db related unittests to proper places

It is expected, that unittests cover project modules in relation 1:1 and
placed in appropriate tree as main modules do.

It should be like in example:
manila/[tests/]foo/bar/[test_]modulename.py

Change-Id: I890deaeb41b87a6ae82868905144fd7477272058
Partial-Bug: #1348633

commit_message:
Send back testing results

As a CI tool Solum should be able to report testing
results back to user. This patch handles the case of
hosting code on Github. By leveraging Github API,
Solum can send back the statuses of testing, i.e.
pending/success/failure and a log url for user to
inspect results.

A Github OAuth token is used for posting statuses.
The token will need to be generated by a user and
put into Solum plan file.

Closes-bug: 1365651

Change-Id: I223418f63d663a9673963b1f6a7a4367bd1766e1

commit_message:
Don't allow security service to be updated if used

When we attach security service to share network and create
share server associated with this share network, security service
or share-network should not be updated as well as deleted.

For update should be available only 'name' and 'description' fields.

Don't allow to remove assigned security-service from share-network
when share-servers exist.

Add unit and tempest tests.

Change-Id: Ide82edea355030b281dc709f8545abfd0fcd13fb
Closes-bug: #1357355

commit_message:
Implement wait-after policy and retry

 * This allows to add wait-after policy to task
   and value of delay to wait.
 * Small fixes in direct_workflow
 * Added workflow_trace logging
 * Unit tests
 * Improve BaseEngineTest to work on
   fake rpc_backend

Implements blueprint mistral-workflow-wait-policy
Implements blueprint mistral-retry-policy

Change-Id: Ib1163635315acc5c2aabfb1ea59a2e6aff8558b0

commit_message:
Add GlusterFS protocol as a supported Share/NAS type

This patch adds GlusterFS as a supported protocol (in addition
to NFS and CIFS) in the Share/NAS type doc/help string. Since the
Manila server side now support cert based access type which
introduced 'glusterfs' as a new share protocol, this patch
updates the manilaclient help/doc string to reflect the same.

'glusterfs' protocol support was added to server side using:
https://review.openstack.org/116859

Change-Id: I94cbecd55fabbfd1bb7c06184e4679c7531d0214
Closes-Bug: #1367205

commit_message:
Avoid URL-encoding of values

Mustache will URL-encode values containing certain characters if a
double brace is used. EG "Secr<tP'ss" encodes as "Secr<tP'ss".
This is probably undesirable in all config files.

The Ex command used to apply this:

    :silent! %s/{\@<!{{\([^{#^\/].\{-}\)}}/{{{\1}}}/g

The Vim macro used to fix merge conflicts, as I expect I'll have to use
this more than once before this merges:

    /<<<<<<^MV/======^M:s/{\@<!{{[#/^{]\@!/{{{/g^M
    :'<,'>s/\({{{[^}]*}}\)}\@!/\1}/g^M
    ?<<<<<<^Mdd/======^MV/>>>>>>^Md

Change-Id: I667cda250aaf4e9d9cb76d971665d22cbd7681a5

commit_message:
Propose a more generic volume migration approach

This will allow the RBD driver and others that don't support iSCSI
attachment to support volume migration.

Related blueprint: generic-volume-migration

Change-Id: I33b1019ed6c690bd5fe9a01365c7666cc0413af2

commit_message:
Unify the sensor data format

Ceilometer will consider the 'Sensor Reading' data contains the unit in
the end of current value, ipmitool driver returns such format, however our
ipminative driver returns the 'Sensor Reading' value without the unit, so we
have to unify them for Ceilometer to provide same sensor data format.

Closes-Bug: #1367620

Change-Id: I6796bf513730259b7a27715252a72879b11d3bae

commit_message:
Switch to using pbr's autodoc capability

Once we use the pbr based build to generate files, we prune
the indexes to remove references to code we would like to
hide like the common modules and private modules in conf.py.
We reuse the same excluded_patterns variable that is already
used in Sphinx and filter these modules from autoindex.rst

Change-Id: I777bdeaee5332a73ee39bc5bdc832bd0140724ce

commit_message:
Send more than 1 message in messages_get_many

A bug in falcon prevented this test to be meaningful. That bug has been
fixed and now we can serialize several messages ids in a query
parameter.

Change-Id: I5887509617d87661794f9c350057c24c16f4e868

commit_message:
Remove unused modules from openstack-common.conf

openstack-common.conf under "The list of modules to copy from
oslo-incubator" section contains some modules that are not used by
Ironic code, only by openstack/common modules. Such modules should be
removed from openstack-common.conf, as oslo-incubator/update.py can
handle internal dependencies.

Change-Id: Ifb3cc67efba10dd39e86c1d3a0cc769753de2122
Closes-bug: #1367291

commit_message:
Symlink /etc/my.cnf instead of deleting it

All of the existing mariadb elements install from packages. /etc/my.cnf
is a packaged file, and it shouldn't be deleted as rpm does not provide
a way to "mark" a file as intentionally deleted.  Instead of deleting
it, create a symlink to the config we actually use at /etc/mysql/my.cnf.

Change-Id: I3909cd8fbd77a9121f4e3ba4d40eae799207bff9

commit_message:
Add -c support to devtest_undercloud.sh.

This is similar to the support in devtest_seed.sh. USE_CACHE is
still honored for backwards compatibility.

Change-Id: Iac5ffceadc15a09ba82c09573c0101941ddc31cc

commit_message:
Set flavor id for Ironic's baremetal flavor

An existing trove bug prevents it from functioning when Nova flavors exist
with an id that is a UUID instead of an integer, causing Tempest failures.
This sets an integer ID when creating the baremetal flavor for Ironic's use.

Change-Id: Ic090f61a9a47421117dc86b640422f00f468112c
Related-bug: #1333852

commit_message:
Specify correct operation type when NVH is raised

When nova-conductor received a NoValidHost (NVH) exception for a
cold migrate or resize operation, its error message back through
the API layer always displayed the string "cold migrate" in the
error text, even when the operation was a resize. This leads to
potentially confusing situations when triaging problems in the
cloud environment.

This patch corrects the error message based on the operation; we use
the flavor IDs as a way to determine what operation is really being
performed. In the case of a resize, different flavor IDs will be
used and they will be indentical in the case of a cold migration.

Note there was a lot of IRC discussion on this as well in terms of
the "algorithm" to check the operation type; the flavor ID check
is also used in the API layer as well since it's the only way you
can determine this given the underlying operation.  We also tried
to make the error message more general, but the consensus was that
was pretty unfriendly from the user's perspective - so we've landed
with this approach again with the end users close to heart.  :-)

Change-Id: I762425b2602c2798b94d3c770f2401dd0aedc942
Closes-Bug: #1364692

commit_message:
Use oslosphinx and remove local copy of doc theme

A packaging review in Fedora found that we had a copy of jQuery code.
Apparently, other OpenStack projects applied a patch to remove this
code, but Manila forked Cinder code from before. The across-the-board
change in OpenStack missed Manila, because we weren't incubated yet.

This patch is almost an exact copy of Cinder patch, but not cherry-
picked because of additional changes, such as the move from oslo.sphinx
to oslosphinx.

Patch is verified to produce readable documentation.

Change-Id: Id0b57f89ae6b63b26b7f0c3fa9af5a529e92ac69

commit_message:
Explain why we look for passwords in $CWD first

The logic added in I30a2cc4f406122bb038d314a277c2444182bd0c9 is not
always entirely clear to people reading the code, which has led to some
confusion when other people are working on the same code.

This change adds comments which attempt to explain the logic being used
here, and mention some of the reasons why we want this behaviour.

Change-Id: I12d013196b0c533a0550167b9b8209e590e3bd49

commit_message:
Change keystone memcache backend

Use keystone memcache pool backend
in order to fix scalability and
failover problems

Also fixing file_line "match" + "after" insertion logic.

Change-Id: Idfe4b54caa0d96a93e93bfff12d8b6216f83e2f1
Closes-bug: #1364401
Closes-bug: #1340657

commit_message:
Add Ironic sideways migration testing

This adds the ability for grenade to be used to run a 'sideways'
upgrade within the Juno release to migrate nodes from Nova Baremetal
to Ironic.  The process is as follows:

  * Deploy base Nova with VIRT_DRIVER=fake, stop base.
  * Deploy target with VIRT_DRIVER=ironic
  * Create Nova baremetal nodes and interfaces in db that map to
    VMs
  * Run Ironic migration scripts to migrate Nova baremetal nodes and
    interfaces to Ironic
  * Update baremetal flavor to reference Ironic deployment ramdisk
    and kernel
  * Run smoke tests against target

Change-Id: Icca6ed4d304c5177a8e41db14c85354d73f10edf

commit_message:
labs: remove linux-image-extra

On Ubuntu 14.04 LTS, the removal of the old kernel (linux-image) fails
after the upgrade because linux-image-extra depends on it. Remove that
package first (if it is installed).

Change-Id: I17a0caa091fd69951df65c4f1ac954a61ea29227

commit_message:
labs: disable cloud-archive for trusty

Icehouse packages are part of Ubuntu 14.04 LTS (trusty), trying to add
the cloud-archive results in an error. The code is still needed for
precise (Ubuntu 12.04) and presumably for trusty once Juno and later
OpenStack releases become available.

Change-Id: I970f938281f0abfc32a3e0c1467c2dca11dfa676

Fix LIBVIRTD_GROUP for opensuse and sles

opensuse is similar to sles and also has libvirt as group
name. Adjust case.

Um, I'm not at all excited about supporting both :)  In my opinion, there should be one obvious way to do thingsand it's actually the core of my argument that we should use action="append" style commands, because that's the way you do this with argparse :)'}, {'account_id': 1525, 'date': '2014-08-21 19:44:34.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

I have no problem ripping out --fields and replacing it with --field everywhere.  I was assuming we'd need both to avoid breaking any scripting folks might be doing against the CLI tool. 

So, I'll alter my offer to submit a patch which replaces --fields everywhere in fav multiple --field calls.  I think it's out of scope for this patch but I agree it's a cleaner implementation and will take on the work."}, {'account_id': 679, 'date': '2014-08-21 19:56:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

So, let me be clear: In this case, where we're introducing a new argument, I prefer to go with one action="append"-style argument.  However, in the case where we already have a .split(',')-style argument, we *do* need to preserve backwards compatibility; so that patch will need to preserve that while adding the action="append"-style functionality.  My suggestion for that case is, if len(args.fields) == 1 and ',' in args.fields[0], then do the split.'}, {'account_id': 1849, 'date': '2014-09-09 18:54:18.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review+2 Workflow+1

commit_message:
Enhance network-list to allow --fields

Add the ability to specify --fields, using any valid vields, when
doing a network-list. This code was shamelessly borrowed from
do_list(). This will allow crafting network-list queries which
mirror the functionality of 'nova-manage network list', which this
query was intended to replace.

Change-Id: I7ec7066350cdb979a64d20d14362b12e3ec76496

commit_message:
Add specific pass-through config for each role

Supplement ExtraConfig with specific versions - ControllerExtraConfig and
NovaComputeExtraConfig. This allows the user to specify different
configurations for each role.

[{'created': '2014-08-28 09:54:48.000000000', 'message': 'VMware: Remove get_copy_virtual_disk_spec from vmops and vm_util

VMwareVMOps.get_copy_virtual_disk_spec() became a no-op with the
removal of VMwareVCVMOps. This change removes it, and consequently
removes the copy_spec argument to vm_util.copy_virtual_disk, as it was
only ever being passed None.

We also remove vm_util.get_copy_virtual_disk_spec(), which is no
longer called at all after the removal of VMwareVCVMOps.

Change-Id: Ibdc6127143c39b084ea956950503af842a72dc24

'}, {'created': '2014-09-02 14:04:27.000000000', 'message': 'VMware: Remove get_copy_virtual_disk_spec from vmops and vm_util

VMwareVMOps.get_copy_virtual_disk_spec() became a no-op with the
removal of VMwareVCVMOps. This change removes it, and consequently
removes the copy_spec argument to vm_util.copy_virtual_disk, as it was
only ever being passed None.

We also remove vm_util.get_copy_virtual_disk_spec(), which is no

commit_message:
VMware: Remove get_copy_virtual_disk_spec from vmops and vm_util

VMwareVMOps.get_copy_virtual_disk_spec() became a no-op with the
removal of VMwareVCVMOps. This change removes it, and consequently
removes the copy_spec argument to vm_util.copy_virtual_disk, as it was
only ever being passed None.

We also remove vm_util.get_copy_virtual_disk_spec(), which is no
longer called at all after the removal of VMwareVCVMOps.

Change-Id: Ibdc6127143c39b084ea956950503af842a72dc24

commit_message:
Enable monitoring of periodic tasks

This task touches a heartbeat file. Monitoring tools can then check the
mtime of that file as a proxy for the health of periodic tasks and hence
the process overall. Without this patch, it is difficult for monitoring
to do more than check the process is running.

Change-Id: I51fa1e70d4613bc1b17fb4c303d8af07817a0802

commit_message:
Update oslo.messaging to latest version

Fixes from 1.4.0.0a3 to 1.4.0.0a5 include:
6ea3b12 Imported Translations from Transifex
fbee941 An initial implementation of an AMQP 1.0 based messaging driver
a9ec73f Switch to oslo.utils
48a9ba4 Fix Python 3 testing
265b21f Import oslo-incubator context module
f480494 Import oslo-incubator/middleware/base
7381ccd Should not send replies for cast messages
4cb33ec Port to Python 3
710dd17 Sync jsonutils from oslo-incubator
2464ca0 Add parameter to customize Qpid receiver capacity
220ccb8 Make tests pass with random python hashseed
92d5679 Set sample_default for rpc_zmq_host
dd1d6d1 Enable PEP8 check E714
ec9ffdb Enable PEP8 check E265
8151da8 Enable PEP8 check E241
ba5b547 Fix error in example of an RPC server
7fdedda Replace lambda method _
500f1e5 Enable check for E226
63a6d62 Updated from global requirements
bea9723 Add release notes for 1.4.0.0a4
d020cb8 Add release notes for stable/icehouse 1.3.1 release
5be1b6a Enabled hacking checks H305 and H307
6684565 Bump hacking to version 0.9.2
1cc3e5d Fixes incorrect exchange lock in fake driver
39d1917 Imported Translations from Transifex
5fbb55b Add missing docs for list_opts()
503b48a Synced jsonutils and its dependencies from oslo-incubator

Change-Id: I1340127f8dac98912170ed0c8d70ec2fa9c89f8c

Ironic driver way point one

This review is not intended to be merged. It is being inserted into
the review chain so we can approve the scheduler filters, but
continue to hold on the ironic driver itself.

commit_message:
Add Windows SMB Volume Driver

Introduces a volume driver which makes use of SMB shares for hosting
volumes as disk images, having a similar workflow with the other NFS
like drivers.

This driver is based on the SMB Volume driver proposed for Linux,
overriding the platform specific methods.

It includes all the features required by the Juno release.

Driver cert results:
http://paste.openstack.org/show/100600/

The online snapshot related tests have been skipped as this
feature is not supported yet.

Change-Id: Idd5964690bca618c11fd116f80dd802d6cc2f31b
Implements: blueprint windows-smbfs-volume-driver

commit_message:
Set default pool value to system in gpfs driver

The configuration option gpfs_storage_pool is assigned with
default value of None. And it gets initialized with None
instead of system, where as the intention is to set the default
value as system.

This change sets default value of gpfs_storage_pool to system
instead of None.

DocImpact

Needs an update in gpfs driver documentation, as this patch
proposes a change in default value of configuration option
(gpfs_storage_pool)

Change-Id: Ib4c2a2e4593a940ae563d329fd59d2d5fe3d4520
Closes-Bug: #1365474

commit_message:
Remove pinning of requests for os-collect-config

We pinned requests to not use version 2.4.0 due to a bug in requests.
2.4.1 has been released now which fixes this issue.

Change-Id: I53f6ff92400b30e9faee186ae8fee9e4e6d0b127

commit_message:
Fix v2 requests to non-bleeding edge servers

In the case where v2 requests are sent to a server which is not running
head of tree which includes the v2 metadef code some 404 cases need to
be handled to enable standard requests to complete.

Change-Id: I3a961d2d3d0e4aad81f92f983e0b20c2d9fa54ca
Closes-bug: #1367326

subject: VMware: Add check for datacenter with no datastore

commit_message:
VMware: Add check for datacenter with no datastore

When there is a datacenter with no datastore in it,
nova boot fails.

This patch addresses the issue by adding a check
and ignoring the empty datacenter.

closes-bug: #1302482
(cherry picked from commit 529e7d14a716fcc1264b2e8053be3c842afd2153)

Conflicts:

	nova/tests/virt/vmwareapi/test_vmops.py

Change-Id: I3c8242767f5991d4aeffab09c763a21493fc363e

commit_message:
VMware: Disable suds caching

The default cache implementation in suds store pickled objects in a
predictable path in /tmp which could lead to attacks. This patch
turns off suds caching to address this security issue.

Conflicts:
        cinder/volume/drivers/vmware/pbm.py

Change-Id: I7daaa25a0677004e03896298e9c3026d5c33c6ac
Closes-Bug: #1341954
(cherry picked from commit 6a41fe9c5c98a14a355fa81b41aae2c4b0ce0a7b)

commit_message:
Ironic driver fetches extra_specs when needed

The Ironic driver needs to access flavor['extra_specs'] in certain
situations. This access was erroneously removed during the large patch
series to land the driver in Nova. The corresponding change did not land
in Ironic, because it fails to pass tempest (as does the current Ironic
driver in Nova).

This patch reverts that change.

Change-Id: I525c611aa0e98076477c2a9a279a0f8a47858aac
Closes-bug: 1367007

commit_message:
Increase the quotas for nodepool on hp1

Allow hp1 to support up to 150 nodes, increasing the RAM quota to
1300000 will roughly achieve this. The other values are increased
so they don't get in the way (without being unlimited which will
hopefully prevent possible leaks).

Change-Id: I7c6a28ade7d60b7e8d69ad43f5f2eaef80ac0ae1

commit_message:
Add PostDeployNodeActions class and PostPatchingHA hook

Add new class for post deployment actions for each node.
This class, in comparison to PostDeployActions executes
hooks immediately after each node group is deployed on
the nodes of this group.

Add PostPatchingHA hook that executes on controller nodes
and unbans particular nodes for OpenStack pacemaker services.

Change-Id: I290556693c8022a2b2cfc53df2180db66e935348
Related-bug: #1364068

commit_message:
Explicitly set swift bind_port(s) in .conf files

The swift service is in the process of making it a requirement to
explicitly specify the bind_port for account, container & object
servers in their .conf files. See
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/118200/ for details.

The swift configuration in tripleo relies on default ports being
set by the swift service. Without these defaults swift in tripleo
will not function correctly.

This patch explicitly sets bind_port in the swift .conf files.

The bind_ports specified in the swift .conf files, if required
can be overridden using the tripleo passthrough mechanism.

This change also removes the use of hard coded swift port values
in elements/swift/os-refresh-config/configure.d/73-swift. With this
patch the ports are set in the .conf files and don't need to be
defaulted in 73-swift.

Change-Id: I0a8c3862f23f74e162ee384cf257e6e5930cde01

commit_message:
Move Zake driver code to separated Python module

That is needed to prevent Zake driver load in real-life Zookeeper
usage - currently we had the situation when even if you want to use
just KaZoo, you needed to install partially test-requierements
(zake package).

Change-Id: I9664fda2d6e76a6e48776b4a6d92af4c4baf1425

commit_message:
Fix auto-filled object names enabling upload button

Affect Swift object storage file upload in Horizon.

This fix ensures that the user no longer needs to manually type
into the Object Name field to prompt the Upload button to become
enabled when the Object Name field has been automatically filled
with the name of the chosen file.

Change-Id: I11ea55cdf3aa6d0754d9e31510ff004bfa914bc1
Closes-Bug: 1348404

commit_message:
Swap Fn::Join for Fn::Replace wherever we can

A lot of our Fn::Join use was in building formatted strings such as database
addresses, API URLs and /etc/hosts entries. These are more clearly and
succinctly expressed with Fn::Replace uses a template-based approach.

Since Fn::Join does not exist in HOT, this moves us closer to porting our
templates over. What remains are operations that join lists returned by Heat or
Merge::Map into a single (usually '\n' separated) string. We can just return the
raw data instead (e.g. a list instead of a processed string) and format them
with os-apply-config.

Change-Id: I2ed953dab288400b6ddc1b31466546a323d225b5

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks

    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be

    participate in the community the more rewarding it is for you. You may also
    notice that the more you get to know people and get to be known, the faster
    your patches will be reviewed and eventually approved. Get to know others
    and become known by doing code reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a
    great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

commit_message:
Fix regression in Cinder volume type creation

The local-vars cleanup (Iedeafa15def1fa26d4ddcbc5f670129f66e38b9d)
spanned (and missed) this fix (Ib35ffc09f6582354010ac8ca35da581ea508877a)
for volume type creation.

Change-Id: I2b95cbc946727d7708283eca0c07ba1eaddf5db8

commit_message:
Add check_mk swift proxy diagnostic

Added a check_mk script that runs healthcheck to ensure that a
proxy node is up and running with proxy services. This diag is
also check_mk compliant (ie. the output matches check_mk desired
format).

Have not added thecheck_mk-agent element to element-deps file as
even though it is required to install the file itself into the build
image, it can be manually added to images that require diagnostics.

Change-Id: If18acfa1b5c967481f59b9f2041d8d7c37db15ca

commit_message:
Fixes Hyper-V boot from volume root device issue

Checks that instances are booting from volume by checking
the correct root device obtained from the block device info.

Change-Id: I94941dfe96c1596c8e9b91df3d3d19d33ae7fe92
Co-Authored-By: Zsolt Dudas <zdudas@cloudbasesolutions.com>
Closes-Bug: #1357972

commit_message:
Distinguish between name not provided and incorrect

When loading from config we need a way to determine if a plugin name was
specified incorrectly or was not specified at all. We need this to
determine if we need to load a fallback plugin.

This is much more in line with how CLI loading works and how it should
have worked initially.

Change-Id: I5547b6e169abc4f1850ff205a8f054a617785c2c
Closes-Bug: #1359618

commit_message:
Sync oslo lockutils to nova

The commit to be merged:

942e1aa Use file locks by default again
ac995be Fix E126 pep8 errors
15b8352 Remove oslo.log from lockutils

942e1aa is hopefully the fix for the "n-cpu stop about 15 minutes 
before the rest of the test run" problem at the gate. We need to 
make sure this actually fixes the gate problem

Closes-Bug: #1349452

Change-Id: I31265d4e08245879ad72d3e91dcd8be2359ca811

commit_message:
Fix Keystone middleware example in the docs

The docs and sample config use keystonemiddleware.auth_token, but the
correct name is keystoneclient.middleware.auth_token. Let's fix this to
avoid problems when someone uses the example config.

Change-Id: If7f0075c10e5260155f447f894c9dce1d26e0202

commit_message:
Allow user to keep virsh instances alive

Any call to devtest_testenv.sh attempts to remove all virsh instances
defined in that test environment. A user might want to configure a set
of VMs manually for use in the undercloud and overcloud later on, but
still take advantage of the functionality provided by _testenv.sh

This patch adds an optional parameter to devtest_testenv which, if
supplied, skips the destruction of UC and OC VMs. A user who does this
will have to provide their own nodes.json which describes the VMs they
have created. The seed VM is still destroyed and recreated as it is
unlikely to need any customisation. This makes the VM-deploy and
BM-deploy more aligned, in that you can have a set of predefined nodes
for your tripleo system and boot a generic seed to deploy onto them.

Part of bp targeted-node-deployment

Change-Id: If7679d74108bc7064df268c240df5fff6a76d69b
